<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 00:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sierra Leone Diamond Embargo Mulled  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Britain is proposing that the U.N.
Security Council impose a diamond embargo on Sierra Leone to
prevent rebels from financing their renewed war against the
government, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Britain is expected to circulate a draft resolution in the next
few days recommending an embargo be imposed on all diamond sales
that aren't certified by the government, British and U.S. officials
said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   There is no certification process in place now, so the embargo
would cover all diamond exports from the war-weary West African
nation until a program certifying the government origin of the
diamonds is created, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The council is considering the embargo as a way of strangling
the Revolutionary United Front rebels' access to money and weapons.
The London-based organization Global Witnesses estimates that
rebels earned $200 million a year from 1991-1999 in diamond sales,
which they used to buy arms. They have used the supplies to break a
peace agreement signed last year and resume fighting against the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Rebels control roughly 90 percent of the country's diamond
mines, with many of the gems passing through neighboring Liberia
and into the world's diamond markets. The rebels took 500 U.N.
hostages last month, two days after the United Nations announced it
was deploying to the key diamond-mining town of Koidu, which is
held by the RUF.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear how the council would deal with the Liberian
trade, since President Charles Taylor, an ally of RUF leader Foday
Sankoh, was instrumental last month in securing the release of the
captured U.N. peacekeepers. The British official said the council
would have to create a monitoring mechanism to ensure the ban is
being respected -- including by Taylor -- and to spotlight any
violations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
