<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Corrects Border Story  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, Ariz. (AP) -- In a June 1 story about border construction,
The Associated Press erroneously reported which federal agency
temporarily halted the Border Patrol's plans to expand a fence and
build additional roads and lights on the Arizona-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service and the Justice
Department, not the Environmental Protection Agency, halted those
projects for up to 60 days to complete additional environmental
studies.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Gov. Jane Hull's press secretary acknowledged her office
released the erroneous information to the media.
</P>
<P>
   The AP also incorrectly identified Border Patrol spokesman
Charles Klingberg as an EPA spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-06-00 0105 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000606.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mariners 6, Rockies 2  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Alex Rodriguez hit a three-run homer and Edgar
Martinez followed with a solo shot as the Seattle Mariners beat the
Colorado Rockies 6-2 on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The game featured the American and National League players of
the month in May -- Edgar Martinez and Todd Helton. Martinez had the
better day with a double and his 18th homer. Helton went 0-for-4 to
lower his major league-leading average to .410.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez went 3-for-3, and is 5-for-7 with a double, a triple
and a home run over the last two games.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Sele (6-2) allowed one unearned run and five hits in seven
innings to win his fourth straight decision. He matched his season
high with seven strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Leading 2-1 in the fourth, the Mariners jumped on Colorado
starter Masato Yoshii (1-7) for four runs after two outs.
</P>
<P>
   Rickey Henderson singled, Mike Cameron doubled him to third and
Rodriguez followed with his 16th homer. Martinez followed his
homer, the third time the Mariners have hit back-to-back home runs
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii allowed six runs and eight hits in 3 2-3 innings. Scott
Karl pitched the final 4 1-3 innings for Colorado, allowing no runs
and two hits.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Goodwin opened the game with a single off Sele. He stole
second and advanced to third on a throwing error by catcher Dan
Wilson. Neifi Perez followed with a sacrifice fly to make it 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle answered in the first with a run. Henderson walked,
stole second, advanced to third on a flyout and scored on a wild
pitch. Yoshii walked three in the first but escaped a bases-loaded
jam by getting David Bell to foul out.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez singled to start the third, advanced to third on a
double by Martinez and scored on John Olerud's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Mayne hit a solo homer in the ninth off Jose Mesa for
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Helton is hitting .500 at home and .327 on the road. ...
Martinez is hitting (11-for-29) with four homers and eight RBIs
against the Rockies. ... Martinez's first-inning walk was the 900th
of his career. ... The crowd of 25,582 is the second smallest ever
in 70 games at Safeco Field. ... Seattle's first five batters went
9-for-18 (.500). ... Yoshii's 3 2-3 innings matches his shortest
outing of the season. ... The Rockies are 1-5 in Seattle, and this
was their first game at Safeco Field.
</P>
</TEXT>
