<DOCNO> APW20000606.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Violence Reported in Solomon Islands  </HEADLINE>
By RAY LILLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) -- Fighting broke out Tuesday
between rival islanders in the Solomon islands, which were thrown
into a crisis a day earlier when armed rebels seized the prime
minister and demanded his ouster, officials in New Zealand said.
</P>
<P>
   One fight involving about 1,000 people was reported near
Henderson Field, the airport outside the Solomon Islands capital of
Honiara, according to a New Zealand official who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting had died down after a couple of hours and although
New Zealand Foreign Minister Phil Goff characterized it as ''more
of a skirmish than a battle'' with only four people known to have
been wounded, he was worried about an unstable situation.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a clear warning that things could get much worse quite
quickly,'' Goff told The Associated Press by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   A journalist reached by telephone in the Solomon Islands said
fighting had broken out both east and west of Honiara, and at least
four people were believed to have been wounded from one side.
</P>
<P>
   The official and the journalist both spoke to the AP only on
condition their names not be used.
</P>
<P>
   The reported fighting came a day after Prime Minister
Bartholomew Ulufa'alu was seized -- the latest move in inter-island
fighting that has shaken this nation for 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   The Solomons are located 2,230 miles northwest of Wellington and
1,600 miles northeast of Sydney, Australia. The Malaita Eagle Force
and the Isatabu Freedom Movement rebel groups have been fighting
for 18 months on the nation's main island of Guadalcanal -- the
scene of a fierce battle between U.S. and Japanese forces in World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   The Isatabu force has been fighting to push thousands of
migrants from the nearby island of Malaita off of Guadalcanal. The
Malaita rebels are resisting the Isatabu's effort, and at least 50
people have been killed or left missing in the fighting and 20,000
forced to flee their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Honiara, located on Guadalcanal, is largely populated by
Malaitans, including Ulufa'alu -- who is viewed by some Malaitans as
a turncoat.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Andrew Nori, a spokesman for the Malaita rebels who has
been identified in some reports as the attempted coup leader, said
Monday that Ulufa'alu was being held at home in ''protective
custody'' after being captured by six gunmen from the Malaita Eagle
Force.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to seizing Ulufa'alu, the Malaita rebels overran
police stations and the Government Telecommunications Center in
Honiara early Monday, Australian officials said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the government caucus of the Solomon Islands
reconvened a meeting to consider a motion that could oust Ulufa'alu
from office -- the Malaita rebels' goal.
</P>
<P>
   Ulufa'alu showed up at the meeting accompanied by two armed
guards who had seized him. He told a reporter for the Solomon
Islands Broadcasting Co. ''I'm all right,'' according to a report
placed on the broadcaster's Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   Ulufa'alu had offered last week to resign as his support
dwindled, but the necessary government meeting never took place
because officials from around the sprawling island nation did not
arrive on time.
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand diplomats in Honiara were trying to broker
conciliatory talks, but information out of the Solomon Islands was
scarce because telephone and air links had been cut off after the
series of rebel raids on Monday. At least some telephone services
were restored by Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Malaita rebels had at least four of their men wounded in
Tuesday's fighting, and they were brought to hospitals in Honiara,
the Solomon Islands journalist said. It was not clear if there had
been any casualties on the Isatabu side, the journalist said.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent coup attempt was the second in the South Pacific in
weeks. In Fiji, armed rebels are still holding the deposed prime
minister and more than 30 other people seized in a raid on
parliament on May 19.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
