<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAS Passes Resolution on Peru  </HEADLINE>
By TOM COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDSOR, Ontario (AP) -- The Organization of American States has
voted to work on strengthening democracy in Peru but stopped short
of questioning the South American nation's tainted presidential
election or imposing sanctions -- a decision likely to anger human
rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   The organization of 34 Western Hemisphere nations made the
decision after participating foreign ministers spent much of Monday
-- the second day of a three-day OAS meeting -- focusing on Peru.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution the ministers passed takes no punitive steps
against Peru. It notes, though, that problems in the voting that
re-elected President Alberto Fujimori showed deficiencies in Peru's
electoral process and democratic institutions.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said it was more important to join other OAS
states in trying to promote democracy in the region than to push
for a tougher response.
</P>
<P>
   ''The focus of our attention today must be on resolving this
crisis of credibility in Peru,'' said Thomas Pickering, the U.S.
undersecretary of state for political affairs. He said the U.S.
government reserves the right to impose sanctions if Peru resists
the OAS push for reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori was re-elected in a runoff election May 28 that
featured himself as the only candidate. His opponent boycotted the
runoff, alleging the election was rigged, and independent monitors
refused to observe the vote because it failed to meet basic
international standards of fairness.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's resolution was authored by host Canada. It orders an
investigative mission of two -- OAS Secretary General Cesar Gaviria
of Colombia and Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy --
to leave for Peru ''immediately'' to work on ways to strengthen
democracy there. Specific study issues include reforming the
electoral process and bolstering freedom of the press.
</P>
<P>
   Axworthy said he and Gaviria would go to Peru prior to
Fujimori's inauguration July 28, when opposition groups plan to
hold a major protest rally in Lima.
</P>
<P>
   Debate before the vote pitted Peru and some Latin American
allies that oppose foreign intervention in election issues against
the United States and others seeking a harsh response to
irregularities in the Peruvian voting.
</P>
<P>
   ''Latin America as a whole is affected by any backsliding with
respect to democracy by any of our countries,'' Marie Alvear of
Chile said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the resolution was a compromise. Peruvian Foreign
Minister Fernando Trazegnies said his country welcomed the OAS
delegation as a forward-looking mission that would avoid any
consideration of the recent election.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution was likely to disappoint groups that wanted the
OAS to suspend Peru or otherwise pressure it to hold new elections.
Human rights groups have warned that protests and violence could
follow if the OAS failed to take strong action.
</P>
<P>
   No protesters turned up at the downtown Windsor meeting site on
Monday, a day after demonstrations by more than 2,000 anti-free
trade activists led to 41 arrests. But at another venue where an
OAS luncheon was held Monday, scores of demonstrators linked arms
and sat down in the rain to block delegates in three buses from
getting inside.
</P>
<P>
   Police had to pick up some of the protesters to clear the road.
No arrests were reported.
</P>
<P>
   The protests Sunday were the largest in memory at an OAS
gathering and brought the group face-to-face with the anti-free
trade movement that disrupted a World Trade Organization meeting in
Seattle in December. The same movement sparked street clashes at an
International Monetary Fund meeting in Washington earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Organization of American States: http://www.oas.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-06-00 0141 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
