<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, June 6, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Indonesian Quake Deaths at 103
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BENGKULU, Indonesia (AP) -- The official death toll from Sumatra's massive
earthquake rose to 103 on Tuesday as the search for victims intensified despite
rumbling aftershocks that kept scared survivors outdoors. Police feared the
number of casualties could rise even further once authorities reach remote
areas, including a tiny island closest to the epicenter of the earthquake, which
struck on Sunday night. Many were crushed as they slept when their poorly built
homes caved in. The magnitude-7.9 quake cut off communications and electricity,
and closed the area's main airport.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Albright Seeks Arafat To Speed Talks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- With Israel hinting of territorial concessions but
complaining of delays by Yasser Arafat, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is
meeting with the Palestinian leader as she tries to move the Middle East peace
process forward. Albright, on the second day of a three-day swing through the
region, was traveling to Ramallah in the West Bank for a meeting today with
Arafat. Afterward, she was returning to Jerusalem for sessions with Barak and
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy. The return visit was announced only Monday
after Albright and Barak met for more than three hours.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Kids' Behavioral Problems Said Soar
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- New research suggests that the number of U.S. youngsters with
emotional and behavioral problems soared in the past two decades, in part
because of more poor and single-parent households. The findings, echoing other
recent studies, are based on surveys of pediatricians on more than 21,000
patients. The researchers said it is not a case of doctors getting better at
recognizing and diagnosing emotional and behavioral problems. Instead, they said
there is a real increase in such problems among youngsters. The researchers
found that problems such as attention deficit/hyperactivity disorder, depression
and learning disabilities more than doubled from 1979 to 1996.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Praises Chernobyl Shutdown
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) -- President Clinton on Monday praised the announcement
that Ukraine President Leonid Kuchma has ordered the Chernobyl nuclear power
plant to close on Dec. 15. Clinton dispensed $80 million in American aid to
entomb the plant forever. It comes atop about $200 million the United States has
already spent to improve nuclear safety in Ukraine. The April 26, 1986, accident
spread radioactive material over much of Europe. The Ukrainian government has
blamed the disaster for at least 8,000 deaths, including 31 killed immediately,
many more killed in the massive cleanup operation and others who later died of
cancer and other radiation-related illnesses.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Strong Quake Shakes Central Turkey
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- A strong earthquake with a preliminary magnitude of
5.9 shook central Turkey early Tuesday, the Istanbul-based Kandilli Observatory
said. There was no immediate information on whether it caused any injuries or
damage. The epicenter was the town of Cerkez in Cankiri province, 60 miles north
of the capital, Ankara, Kandilli said. The quake, which lasted about 30 seconds,
was felt in Ankara, its environs and along the Black Sea coast.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Sierra Leone Diamond Embargo Mulled
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Britain is proposing that the U.N. Security Council
impose a diamond embargo on Sierra Leone to prevent rebels from financing their
renewed war against the government, officials said Monday. Britain is expected
to circulate a draft resolution in the next few days recommending an embargo be
imposed on all diamond sales that aren't certified by the government, British
and U.S. officials said, speaking on condition of anonymity. There is no
certification process in place now, so the embargo would cover all diamond
exports from the war-weary West African nation until a program certifying the
government origin of the diamonds is created, the officials said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks slipped Tuesday on profit-taking following recent
sharp gains. The Nikkei Stock Average shed 83.88 points to 17,117.91 in the
first 30 minutes of trading. In New York on Monday, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 20.54 at 10,815.30. On the NYSE, decliners led advancers
1,636-1,331. The Nasdaq composite index rose 8.38 to 3,821.76.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mariners Beat Rockies 6-2
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Alex Rodriguez hit a three-run homer and Edgar Martinez
followed with a solo shot as the Seattle Mariners beat the Colorado Rockies 6-2
on Monday night. The game featured the American and National League players of
the month in May -- Edgar Martinez and Todd Helton. Martinez had the better day
with a double and his 18th homer. Helton went 0-for-4 to lower his major
league-leading average to .410. Rodriguez went 3-for-3, and is 5-for-7 with a
double, a triple and a home run over the last two games.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by PAULINE M. MILLARD
</SUBHEAD>
