<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Orbador Leads in Mexico City Race  </HEADLINE>
By JULIE WATSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Six years ago, he rose to national prominence
when what was widely seen as fraud cost him the Tabasco state
governorship, and he organized thousands of people to blockade the
governor's office.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, he appeared in national newspapers bleeding from the
forehead while leading a massive protest to stop Mexico's
state-owned oil company from contaminating poor farmers' cocoa
fields.
</P>
<P>
   Neither protest resulted in any major changes.
</P>
<P>
   Now Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador is waging a new battle as
candidate to govern the Western Hemisphere's largest and possibly
most complex city. The battleground is bigger, but this time it
seems he may win.
</P>
<P>
   Just weeks ago, a federal elections court narrowly voted against
revoking his candidacy for allegedly failing to meet the five-year
residency requirement. Now, the Tabasco state native leads his two
major rivals by 20 percentage points in the polls as he seeks to
become Mexico City mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need a nonconformist,'' said Hugo Vargas Guzman, a
28-year-old taxi driver, weaving his green Volkswagen bug through
traffic, fruit carts, bicycles and pedestrians. ''I think it's a
plus that he's not from here. We need someone who is going to bring
in new ideas, because everything needs to change in this city.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly one third of Mexico City's 9 million people live in
poverty. Pollution hovers around twice the acceptable limit on the
best of days. Crime is so bad that even middle-class families hire
security guards for their homes. And the infrastructure is
crumbling so badly that entire neighborhoods recently flooded with
raw sewage.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor of this former Aztec imperial seat is one of the most
important, visible and criticized elected officials in Mexico. Up
until 1997, the mayor was hand-picked by the president, who since
1929 has been a member of the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   Enshrining a new era of power-sharing, the center-left
Democratic Revolution Party won the first mayoral election three
years ago with the landslide victory of Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, who
resigned last year to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez Obrador was president of Democratic Revolution when
Cardenas was elected. He resigned to run for mayor. With Cardenas
trailing far behind in the presidential polls, Lopez Obrador now is
battling for the life of his party.
</P>
<P>
   ''These elections are crucial for the Democratic Revolution
Party,'' said analyst Alfonso Zarate. ''It's almost a question of
survival for the party because it has no chance at the presidential
level, but it must keep the capital in order to stay alive.''
</P>
<P>
   To recover the capital, the ruling party has turned to party
veteran Jesus Silva Herzog, who contends Lopez Obrador is part of
the problem, not the solution.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent televised debate, Silva Herzog blamed him for the
constant demonstrations that clog traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ''He started the trend of bringing the conflicts of other states
to Mexico City. Don't forget that Andres Manuel brought us the
janitors of Tabasco, that he took over the oil wells and that he
blocked highways,'' Silva Herzog said. ''That's how all this
disorder began.''
</P>
<P>
   A former treasury secretary and ambassador to the United States,
Silva Herzog has largely campaigned on his extensive experience in
government. That asset, analysts say, has also been his downfall in
a city hungry for change.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative National Action Party candidate, Sanitago Creel, a
lawyer-turned-congressman who proposes economic reform and better
tax collection, also has struggled despite the fact that city
residents overwhelmingly favor his party's presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez Obrador seems to have had success by concentrating on the
working-class population, vowing to bring the government closer to
the people.
</P>
<P>
   ''There won't be luxury offices. We will lower salaries of
high-level public servants. We won't buy late-model vehicles. We
won't use bodyguards,'' Lopez Obrador said. ''We can't have a rich
government and a poor people.''
</P>
<P>
   He has carried out an exhaustive run that is headed toward 1,000
campaign stops.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is an excellent candidate, but the question is whether he
will be a good mayor,'' Zarate said. ''Lopez Obrador has no
experience at governing and this is very complex city.''
</P>
<P>
   Some residents believe a rabble rouser is exactly what this city
needs and didn't get when Cardenas snatched the mayorship from the
ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most people felt disappointed by Cardenas because they
expected an abrupt change in the government,'' Zarate said. ''But
Cardenas is an intellectual who may be honest and efficient, but
who has never shined as a leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, his administration went after crooked police
officers and investigated former top officials, leaving a general
sense that the city is less corrupt than it was under the ruling
party.
</P>
<P>
   For some, that was not enough for a city bursting at its seams.
</P>
<P>
   In a poor neighborhood, a city hospital's intensive care section
is so crowded that doctors hop over patients who have been left
lying on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought things were going to get better, but nothing has,''
said Evelia Prado Herrera, 62, waiting for a nurse to tend to her
in the chaotic hospital. ''We need someone who can renovate this
city.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
