<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Destiny Calls Lakers In Finals  </HEADLINE>
By GREG BEACHAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Lakers need four victories to
embrace their apparent destiny. The Indiana Pacers need four wins
to avoid their apparent fate.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA Finals pit the league's latest royalty against a
longtime member of its old guard. Starting with Game 1 on
Wednesday, the Lakers will try to take their biggest step toward
becoming the game's next great team, while the Pacers try to earn
the only honor missing from a lengthy run among the league's elite.
</P>
<P>
   The star-powered, high-gloss Lakers spent the season as the
NBA's main event. Their swagger and skill seemingly mark them as
the heirs to the Chicago Bulls' vacated dynasty. They have a
mastermind coach in Phil Jackson, the inherent glamour of their
hometown and their franchise's playoff legacy of six championships.
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, the Lakers appear to have a limitless future,
with two of the game's superstars, one just reaching the prime of
his career, the other probably years from it. Shaquille O'Neal and
Kobe Bryant became basketball's newest royal couple this season,
when they finally turned their potential into results.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are expecting a lot of us, but it's no more than we
expect of ourselves,'' Bryant said. ''We haven't ever minded being
the favorites. We want that position.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers spent the season fighting the tick of their
basketball clocks. Age, a decade of playoff frustration, the
imminent departures of coach Larry Bird to retirement and several
players to free agency -- everything signals Indiana is almost
certainly making its last run at a title.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've accomplished a whole lot in the course of our time
together, and we've lost to some teams for whatever reasons,''
point guard Mark Jackson said. ''No shame in that. Fortunately, we
don't have to worry about that again, because we knocked through
the door this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiana reached its first finals by earning the Eastern
Conference's best record and the top playoff seed. That meant New
York and Miami -- the Eastern teams thought to pose the toughest
potential challenge to Los Angeles -- had to slug it out in the
conference semifinals. The Pacers disposed of the injury-depleted
Knicks in six games last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers were cruising toward the finals before the Portland
Trail Blazers erased a 3-1 series deficit with two victories.
Portland even led by 15 points in the fourth quarter of Game 7
before Los Angeles mounted a stirring comeback for an 89-84
victory.
</P>
<P>
   But with the drama of the conference finals behind them, the
Lakers look formidable again. Unlike New York or Miami, the Pacers
seem ill-equipped to deal with O'Neal. And as the Lakers proved all
season, when the league MVP plays unfettered, they are close to
unbeatable.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's just a very big, strong man that has a lot of athletic
ability,'' Bird said. ''You have to try to switch up things on the
defensive end, but we don't want to get carried away.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once you start doing a lot of crazy things against Shaq, all
of a sudden Glen Rice is a big factor. ... You can't let other guys
step up and break your back.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiana's aging roster and general lack of athletic ability are
the main reasons the Lakers are a strong favorite in the series.
The Pacers' struggles against quicker, more athletic teams such as
Los Angeles were clear all season.
</P>
<P>
   In the first round of the playoffs, only a desperate 3-pointer
by Travis Best in the waning moments of Game 5 saved Indiana from a
series loss to the Milwaukee Bucks, who play an up-tempo style
similar to that of the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Bird doesn't like double-teaming defensive schemes because his
team's slow rotations frequently leave opponents open for jumpers.
He'll have no choice against O'Neal, who has pounded Indiana center
Rik Smits throughout their careers.
</P>
<P>
   But as dominating as O'Neal can be, the Pacers have their own
offensive star who has been winning playoff games nearly by himself
since Shaq was in college. Reggie Miller, returning to his hometown
to face his favorite childhood team, has his biggest stage yet to
be the man opposing fans love to hate.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's always been a goal of mine to get to the finals and
perform, but it's going to even be sweeter to play against L.A. at
home,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's standout defense notwithstanding, the Blazers proved
the Lakers have serious weaknesses stopping opponents on the
perimeter. Steve Smith and Scottie Pippen scored at will from
outside during much of the conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Portland destroyed the Lakers' indestructible
veneer by stretching them to seven games. Despite the odds the
Pacers face, they enter their first finals knowing their task is
not impossible -- that their title hopes are no more improbable than
the Lakers' aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have a very attractive team,'' Mark Jackson said. ''(But)
I never thought any team in this league was invincible. Everybody
can be beat. They're well aware of it, and so are we.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-06-00 0205 </TRAILER>
