<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Horse Trainer Eddie Gregson Dies  </HEADLINE>
By BETH HARRIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- The apparent suicide of trainer
Eddie Gregson, who saddled 1982 Kentucky Derby winner Gato Del Sol,
has stunned Southern California's horse racing industry.
</P>
<P>
   Gregson, 61, died Sunday of an apparent self-inflicted gunshot
wound. His body was found by his wife, Gail, in his South Pasadena
office, police Sgt. Mark Miller said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said no foul play is suspected. He said police believe
Gregson's death was a suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody at the track is in complete horrified shock,''
trainer Jenine Sahadi said. ''He was a father figure to a lot of
people and that's why it's so unexpected. He was always laughing
and loved to tell stories and loved to hear stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Sahadi said she joked with Gregson on Sunday after he saddled
one of his horses at Hollywood Park. Crows, a 3-year-old, finished
third, beaten by two heads. Street Cat, a 2-year-old filly racing
for the first time, was seventh in her race.
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Fame trainer Bobby Frankel said he knew of no reason why
Gregson would kill himself.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know you get depressed when you lose, but it's got to be
something else. I thought his life was pretty normal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a real good guy, an honest person and very intelligent.
He's a very good trainer. The horses came first with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sahadi, who saddled her first Kentucky Derby starter last month,
said Gregson had been particularly kind to her husband, trainer Ben
Cecil.
</P>
<P>
   ''He did whatever he could to help him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He tried with younger people to make them believe in racing.
He wanted everybody to respect racing and respect the animals. He
wasn't afraid to speak out about things that he thought were
wrong,'' Sahadi said.
</P>
<P>
   Gregson, who lived in Pasadena, went to his office in the
evening after racing ended at the Inglewood track.
</P>
<P>
   ''When he didn't come home and didn't answer the phone, she went
to check on him,'' Miller said. ''He was found by her.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said Mrs. Gregson told police that her husband had been
facing personal problems unrelated to racing.
</P>
<P>
   ''She knew he had been depressed and unhappy for some time,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gato Del Sol, a 21-1 long shot in the 1982 Kentucky Derby,
provided Gregson with his biggest victory. He also trained Super
Diamond, winner of the 1986 Hollywood Gold Cup, who retired in 1989
as the third richest California-bred thoroughbred.
</P>
<P>
   Gregson had 13 victories from 79 starts and earnings of $433,909
last year, with Controlled being his lone stakes winner in the Boo
La Boo at Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   Among Gregson's other major stakes wins were the 1995 Hollywood
Turf Cup with Royal Chariot, the 1989 San Antonio Handicap with
Super Diamond and the 1978 Santa Barbara Handicap with Kittyluck.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Gregson had served as an officer of the
California Thoroughbred Breeders Association and was the current
president of the California Thoroughbred Trainers Association.
</P>
<P>
   Born Aug. 7, 1938, Gregson grew up on his family's ranch and
breeding farm in Ventura County. He graduated from Stanford
University before taking out his trainer's license in 1969 with a
string of horses from Noble Threewitt's stable. Gregson began his
own stable in Southern California in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Gregson also dabbled in acting, working under contract to Warner
Bros. and 20th Century Fox. He appeared in the 1958 war film ''The
Naked and the Dead'' with Cliff Robertson and Raymond Massey.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife and two children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-06-00 0205 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000606.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Meets With Jordan King  </HEADLINE>
By WALTER R. MEARS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- After telling eastern Europeans that the
struggles of building open economies on the ruins of communism will
pay dividends in future prosperity, President Clinton was back at
the White House today, conferring with a leader from the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
   The Oval Office meeting with King Abdullah II of Jordan was the
only event on Clinton's schedule, a day after his return from a
week in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   That was his 48th foreign journey as president; his 49th is
later this week, to Tokyo, for the funeral of a Japanese prime
minister and to meet with his successor.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton returned to Washington from Kiev, Ukraine, Monday night,
ending a journey in which he repeatedly urged openings to the West
for and by Russia and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   At weekend summit meetings with Russian President Vladimir Putin
and in a speech to the Russian parliament on Monday, Clinton said
European unity and institutions should not end at the borders of
the old Soviet Union, but should reach to Moscow and Kiev.
</P>
<P>
   He had sounded the same message to western Europe, in meetings
and speeches in Lisbon, Berlin and Aachen, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The finale was in Kiev, to tens of thousands of Ukranians in the
broad plaza and mall of St. Michael's Square.
</P>
<P>
   ''From Lithuania to Poland to the Czech Republic, those who
chose open societies and open markets like you started out with
sacrifice but they ended up with success,'' Clinton said. ''I
believe Ukraine has the best opportunity in a thousand years to
achieve freedom and prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a presidential performance with a holiday air. Ukranian
rock stars played to the crowd standing in the hot sun, in a
sweeping mall between golden domed cathedrals. A giant American
flag hung over them, hundreds of yards down the mall from the
yellow and blue draped platform where Clinton spoke. The Odessa
Symphony Orchestra was on the plaza at the other side of the
platform. Clinton smiled, kept time and waved at the side of the
conductor when they played ''Take Me Out To The Ball Game.''
</P>
<P>
   He spoke through an interpreter, urging Ukranians to rally in
support of democracy and a reformed, market economy. ''Communism
has lost in Ukraine but a full commitment to free-market democracy
has not yet won,'' he said. ''Do not give up. Keep on fighting.
Boritesya poboroete.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he went to the crowd, shaking hands campaign style along
the barrier in front of the platform. As he finished and headed
home, the bells of blue and white St. Michael's Cathedral, just
rebuilt, rang out over the square.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, with Clinton beside him at the presidential palace,
President Leonid Kuchma announced that the last part of the
Chernobyl nuclear power plant will be closed on Dec. 15, more than
14 years after the worst atomic power accident in history.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced $78 million in U.S. aid for the shutdown, and
said he will seek additional international help for Ukraine. He
promised an additional $2 million in American aid for safety
measures at other Ukranian nuclear plants.
</P>
<P>
   Then the presidents and their official parties toasted the
moment in champagne.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was to make a rapid round trip to Tokyo to attend the
funeral on Thursday of Keizo Obuchi, who died of a stroke on May
14. The Kyodo News Agency said Clinton would hold talks with the
new prime minister, Yoshiro Mori, while he is in Toky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
