<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnians in Iowa Face More Strife  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN BIEMER
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBUQUE, Iowa (AP) -- Mirsad Causevic lost some of the best years
of his life to war. Then he lost his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Now, having made a new life in this town along the Mississippi
River, he and about 110 other refugees from Bosnia-Herzegovina are
facing the loss of their jobs when a meatpacking plant is sold.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what he and other refugees plan to do next, Causevic
grimaces. He has faced the question far too many times.
</P>
<P>
   ''Who knows?'' he said. ''That's very hard to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   The refugees have brought a new perspective to the rich farmland
and forest-covered hills of northeastern Iowa. About 220 Bosnians
had moved to the community by 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''By Dubuque's standards of diversity, this is a major paradigm
shift,'' said Joe Featherston, who works in refugee resettlement
with Catholic Charities in Dubuque. ''I've been working in this
organization 21 years and it is the most diverse this community has
ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   War broke out in Yugoslavia about the time Causevic finished
high school, in 1991. He was pressed into military service.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, Yugoslavia was dissolved and 200,000 people
were either dead or missing. More than 2 million people were made
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ''My generation is a lost generation,'' Causevic said, sipping
thick Bosnian coffee at his Dubuque apartment. ''They had no chance
to get jobs because of the war.''
</P>
<P>
   When it ended in 1995, Causevic was forced to leave his native
Bosnia-Herzegovina, its economy left in tatters by the war.
</P>
<P>
   Causevic, 27, is among about 107,000 refugees from the former
Yugoslavia who have come to the United States since 1992, the State
Department estimates.
</P>
<P>
   As of last year, 4,611 Bosnians were registered with the Iowa's
Bureau of Refugee Services. State officials don't know how many
additional refugees have moved to Iowa from other U.S. cities.
</P>
<P>
   Causevic moved to Dubuque in 1998 to work for Farmland, the
second Bosnian to do so. He started on the production line, but his
hard work and rapidly improving English earned him a promotion to
manager, as well as interpreter, trainer and recruiter for other
Bosnians.
</P>
<P>
   Featherston said changes were required in the city's medical and
social services, courts, law enforcement and schools to accommodate
the newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   Thom Determan, English as a Second Language supervisor for
Dubuque's public schools, said his program has grown threefold
since 1998. There were suddenly about 40 Bosnian students and
Determan had to hire another ESL teacher.
</P>
<P>
   The diversity has enriched Dubuque's schools, Determan said. He
recalls the time a Bosnian child described in class his experience
during the war.
</P>
<P>
   ''The kids were just spellbound,'' he said. ''They never could
imagine a child being through this kind of horrific situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as this community of 58,000 had begun adjusting to its new
members, Featherston said, Farmland announced it would lay off up
to 1,100 workers by this Friday to retool the factory.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything looked like it was going along just so well and the
proverbial rug just got pulled out from under us,'' Featherston
said. ''I really thought we had a kind of permanence in the
making.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bosnians are considering their options: try to find new jobs
in Dubuque; wait for the renovated plant to reopen next year and
hope to be hired back; or move to other towns with meatpacking
plants.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Leary, a supervisor of a free employment training program,
said many Bosnians have expressed interest in intensive ESL and
job-training courses, in fields as diverse as truck driving and
computer programming.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Bernau, an employment consultant for the Greater Dubuque
Development Corp., said officials hope to keep the laid-off
workers, especially since unemployment has dropped below 2 percent
in the Dubuque area.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by Farmland's impending layoffs, the corporation
sponsored a job fair on May 9. Many Bosnians were among the 1,000
people who perused booths set up by dozens of employers and job
service agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The Bosnian community likes Dubuque and doesn't want to leave,
Causevic said. They like the river. They like the hills. And they
like the security they feel, especially for their children.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is actually an excellent place for kids,'' he said. ''My
boy feels free to go out and play with other kids when he gets home
from school. I don't have to worry like in big cities.''
</P>
<P>
   Causevic concedes that language is a factor in the employability
of Bosnians. He said employers also are uncertain of their
immigrant status and whether they might leave.
</P>
<P>
   For refugee Mehmet Dojic, 26, staying in Dubuque depends on
where his next paycheck comes from. ''Maybe I stay, maybe I go. If
I find a new job, I will stay. If not, I will go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Iowa's Bureau of Refugees Services:
http://www.dhs.state.ia.us/Homepages/dhs/refugee
</P>
<P>
   Greater Dubuque Development Corporation:
http://www.greaterdubuque.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-06-00 0209 </TRAILER>
