<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flyers Head: Lindros Dad Not Welcome  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Philadelphia Flyers plan to retain their
rights to Eric Lindros, although the team isn't sure where Lindros
will play next season.
</P>
<P>
   Flyers general manager Bob Clarke, speaking to reporters for the
first time since the Flyers were eliminated from the Eastern
Conference finals on May 26, said the team will make an $8.5
million qualifying offer to Lindros before July 1 to keep him from
becoming a free agent. But Clarke didn't rule out a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we'll call around to see who's interested,'' Clarke
said. ''We're going to make him the qualifying offer; who knows
what happens after that?''
</P>
<P>
   What won't happen, the GM insists, are any more dealings with
Carl Lindros, the former team captain's father-agent.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he comes back, he can't have his dad calling us,'' Clarke
said. ''Every time something happens, his parents get involved:
coaches have to be fired, trainers have to be fired, players have
to be traded. He just has to be responsible for his own play.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he comes back, it's going to be as his own self. We don't
want his mom and dad. We've had enough of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Lindros has suffered six concussions over the past 27
months, and four in the past five months, Clarke believes there are
teams who would be interested in the 27-year-old center.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some of those concussions were diagnosed over the telephone,''
Clarke said. ''Nobody can really tell you about concussions. There
are such a wide variety of medical opinions on them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers also plan to make a decision sometime later this week
on a coach for next season. Craig Ramsay is the favorite. The
Flyers finished the regular season 16-8-1 under Ramsay after coach
Roger Neilson was forced to step aside due to bone-marrow cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Neilson served as a special assistant to Ramsay once he returned
on April 10. He has told Clarke he does not want to return to the
team in any capacity but head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Neilson, asked Monday night about a report he would be hired as
oach of the Calgary Flames, said he knew nothing about such a
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's news to me,'' said Neilson, reached at his Ontario home.
''If the decision goes down that I will not be head coach of the
Flyers, then certainly I'll be asking permission to talk to other
teams, and certainly the Calgary Flames will be one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ''They haven't even named a general manager yet. I have no
knowledge of this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers lost in the Eastern Conference finals to New Jersey,
blowing a made three games to one lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-06-00 0219 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
