<DOCNO> APW20000606.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stars Lose Hunger, Game  </HEADLINE>
By JAIME ARON
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- The Dallas Stars know what they need to do to beat
the New Jersey Devils, because they've done it every game of the
Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, they've had trouble doing it for 60 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas outplayed New Jersey for two periods of Game 4 Monday
night, digging in the corners for pucks and fighting for every inch
of ice to take a one-goal lead. But three goals on three shots in a
span of 3 minutes, 41 seconds sent the Devils to a 3-1 victory and
a similar lead in the series.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars must win Game 5 Thursday night in New Jersey to keep
alive any chance for the Cup to be brought back to Dallas. They
must win the next three -- which they've yet to do in any round this
postseason -- to claim ownership of the trophy for another year.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's possible,'' center Mike Modano said. ''It's been done
before.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars teased themselves into thinking they had a chance to
even the series by showing the extra gear coach Ken Hitchcock
demanded.
</P>
<P>
   Skill players were throwing their bodies around, no one was
giving up on loose pucks and the defense was limiting New Jersey to
long shots that goalie Ed Belfour clearly saw.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Langenbrunner returned from a five-game absence and played
through a painful knee injury. Joe Nieuwendyk also reappeared,
scoring for the first time in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ''We won every battle for two periods,'' forward Jon Sim.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the throttle got jammed.
</P>
<P>
   Great puckhandling and positioning in front of the net led to
New Jersey's first goal, a shorthanded breakaway produced another,
then came the knockout goal while the Stars were still trying to
figure out what happened on the first two.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not what they're doing, it's breakdowns on our part,''
forward Mike Keane said. ''Unfortunately, every mistake we made
tonight ended up in our net.''
</P>
<P>
   The barrage ended Dallas' 7-0 record when Nieuwendyk scores a
point; a streak of nine straight wins following playoff losses; and
Belfour's run of 14 straight home playoff games without allowing
more than two goals. The Stars were 11-0 in postseason when leading
after two periods.
</P>
<P>
   ''We got our heart ripped out from us a little bit today,''
Hitchcock said. ''We went from quite a high to quite a low.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas' resilience has been tested before. The Stars trailed 2-1
in the 2000 Western Conference finals, 3-2 in last year's
conference finals and 1-0 in last year's finals. Nowhere in there,
though, is a two-game comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Of all teams, New Jersey is the least likely to squander such an
opportunity. After all, the Devils just saw Philadelphia fold in
such a situation, so they know exactly what not to do.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not tired and we are not worn out,'' Hitchcock said.
''We are getting beat by a hell of a hockey club right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-06-00 0219 </TRAILER>
