<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 02:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Heads Aims to Shorten Term  </HEADLINE>
By ELAINE GANLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- President Jacques Chirac said he would move to
reduce the presidential term from seven years to five, but wants to
put the issue to the French in a referendum.
</P>
<P>
   The process should be finished by the end of September, he said,
adding that he would halt everything if opponents used the occasion
to seek wider changes or incite political instability.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want an initiative that would change our institutions
and put into question what is most precious -- stability,'' Chirac
said in a television interview Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Reducing the president's office term -- which would require the
constitution be revamped -- has long been a thorny issue, with
successive presidents refusing to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   Political opponents issued a chorus of objections to Chirac's
limitations, saying a constitutional revision should be an occasion
for wider debate.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac also said he did not want to see a limit on the number of
times a head of state could be re-elected under a five-year
mandate. French presidents are currently limited to two mandates, a
maximum 14-year term. The system has been in effect since 1873.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac had long resisted a growing move to reduce the
presidential term, calling it ''an error'' in July.
</P>
<P>
   His change of heart followed growing pressure from Socialist
Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, who said the change was ''essential
to the modernization'' of French political life.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac and Jospin are likely contenders in the next presidential
election in 2002, when the shortened term would take effect. Chirac
will be 69 then.
</P>
<P>
   The president opted to put the issue to a referendum after both
houses of parliament approve a bill specifying the change. Polls
show large public backing for the idea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
