<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 05:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Curbs Grandparents' Rights  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD CARELLI
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT VERNON, Wash. (AP) -- Jenifer Troxel has 10 grandchildren,
but the ones most on her mind are the two she hasn't seen in more
than a year.
</P>
<P>
   There is no telling whether she or her husband, Gary, will see
their granddaughters again following a U.S. Supreme Court ruling
that declared Washington's visitation law too broad.
</P>
<P>
   ''I still have hope,'' Mrs. Troxel said after Monday's 6-3
decision, speaking to reporters at her rural home about 65 miles
north of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just want to see them, period,'' added her husband. ''I
don't see why we can't.''
</P>
<P>
   The girls' father, Brad Troxel, committed suicide in 1993. After
his death, the girls' mother, Tommie Granville, limited their
visits with their paternal grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   The Troxels, both 60, went to court seeking more time with
10-year-old Natalie and 8-year-old Isabelle. They were eventually
awarded visitation of one weekend a month, one week during the
summer and four hours on the girls' birthdays.
</P>
<P>
   However, the U.S. Supreme Court said the state law went too far
in allowing any person to win a court-ordered right to see a child
any time such visitation was found to be in a child's best
interest.
</P>
<P>
   The decision threatens visitation orders won by the Troxels and
other grandparents in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've gotten essentially back to the beginning, so let's just
let these children see their grandparents and get on with their
life,'' said the Troxels' attorney, Mark Olson.
</P>
<P>
   Granville, who did not return a message left at her home in
Anacortes, told The New York Times she considered the case a ''huge
waste of time, money and emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm relieve we finally won,'' she said in today's editions.
''It's a victory over every parent in the country. But I'm just not
sure what we'll do as far as their requests for visits.''
</P>
<P>
   She said there would have been no problem had the grandparents
not sought extended visits. Granville's lawyer, Catherine Smith,
also declined to say whether the grandparents would be allowed to
see the girls.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not a matter of negotiation, and I think that's one
thing the Supreme Court made clear,'' Smith said. ''It's not going
to be decided in the media, and I hope everyone will honor my
client's rights to make these decisions privately, including the
Troxels.''
</P>
<P>
   The high court did not give parents absolute veto power over who
gets to visit their children, disagreeing with part of a ruling by
Washington's highest state court that appeared to do so.
</P>
<P>
   And in finding the state law ''breathtakingly broad,'' Monday's
decision said nothing to directly endanger grandparent-visitation
laws in all 49 other states.
</P>
<P>
   The thrust of the decision is that states must be very careful
in helping grandparents and others with close ties to children win
the right to see them regularly against parents' wishes. Perhaps
most notably, it gave grandparents nationwide no special status in
visitation cases.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Bullock of the conservative Institute for Justice praised
the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ''While one can hardly avoid sympathizing with grandparents who
wish to have contact with their grandchildren, the Supreme Court
thankfully remained focused on the state law's sweeping intrusion
into the family realm,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, courts will be advised not to make use of the
visitation law, said Maureen Hart, an assistant attorney general.
The law could be rewritten by the Legislature, which begins its
next session in January.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the court did not invalidate narrower visitation
laws ''reinforces the notion that there is room for more tailored
approaches that provide to parents the deference the court believes
the constitution affords them in raising their children,'' Hart
said.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the Troxels say they would be satisfied to take
Granville's last visitation offer of one afternoon per month, made
before the case went to the high court.
</P>
<P>
   ''If one afternoon is what we get, we will be happy with that,''
said Jenifer Troxel. ''We just want to be able to see our
grandchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: U.S. Supreme Court decisions:
http://www.supremecourtus.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
