<HEADLINE> Dow Down 62; Nasdaq Up 15  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Market averages were mixed in early trading
today as investors searched for direction in a quiet market.
Continued interest in technology stocks helped the Nasdaq stay in
positive territory for a fourth straight session
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 61.63 to 10,753.67.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Nasdaq composite index
was up 15.18 to 3,836.94, but the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
down 3.16 to 1,464.47.
</P>
<P>
   Intel fell $1.063 to $131.50. The company said it will delay the
launch of its integrated processor, code-named Timna, because of a
conflict with standard memory. The processor, which was expected to
debut in the second half of this year, has now been delayed until
the first quarter of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But a broad range of technology stocks advanced today. Qualcomm
rose 2 to 69\ and PMC-Sierra rose $6.375 to $193.50.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the Nasdaq, Starbucks rose $2.50 to $38.125. The coffee
company will be added to the Staandard &AMP; Poor's 500 on Wednesday,
prompting many index-fund managers to buy the stock so that their
portfolios will continue to mirror the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard fell $3.125 to $117.25, contributing most to the
drop in the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues barely outnumbered advancers on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 134.69 million shares, ahead
of Monday's sluggish pace.
</P>
<P>
   Trading volume remained fairly low as investors opted to wait
for more information on the strength of the U.S. economy before
taking significant new positions. The next potentially
market-moving report will reach traders on Friday, when the Labor
Department releases the Producer Price Index.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 3.43 to 516.73.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.2 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's Xetra DAX index was down 0.8 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.2 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
down 1.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
