<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Donaldson Offers Lighter Side on Web  </HEADLINE>
By ANICK JESDANUN
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- On a recent show about Sports Illustrated's
swimsuit models, Sam Donaldson donned 3-D glasses found in the
magazine. He chatted with supermodel Daniela Pestova and showed
video from the shoot.
</P>
<P>
   On other segments, Donaldson bantered with actress Tracey Ullman
about her new bed and her passion for sleeping. He exchanged double
entendres with comedian Jon Stewart. He recited lyrics to Limp
Bizkit's hip-hop tune ''Nookie,'' sans profanity.
</P>
<P>
   Is this the same Sam Donaldson who reported from the White House
on Jimmy Carter's peace efforts and Ronald Reagan's bullet wounds?
Is this the same Sam Donaldson who interviews the nation's top
political leaders each Sunday on ABC's ''This Week''?
</P>
<P>
   Yes and no.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson is much looser on his Internet-only news program,
which has just expanded from three to five shows a week. It airs at
12:30 p.m. Eastern on ABC News' Web site, although it's available
any time after that.
</P>
<P>
   Because the show draws a younger audience, producers can book
hipper guests and Donaldson can express wit rarely seen on news
shows.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you approach a hard news subject, such as interviewing
the secretary of state about Kosovo, you do it quite seriously,''
Donaldson says. ''On the Web, we're not doing hard news. I'm able
to be looser, if looser means not having to watch every word.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he says, ''If I'm kidding around with (comedian)
Janeane Garofalo, why would I act as if I were interrogating Ronald
Reagan about whether he was selling arms to Iran?''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Panos, a consultant who studies Internet news shows,
worries about credibility. Will viewers who see a goofy Donaldson
on the Web take his serious interviews on TV seriously?
</P>
<P>
   ''Once they've seen it, the cat's out of the bag,'' Panos says.
''People aren't sophisticated enough to handle the expansion of his
human dimension.''
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson and his producers disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's as credible, accurate as ever, but he is also forthright
to a degree people are perhaps not used to seeing,'' says Steve
Jones, executive producer for ABCNews.com. ''What you're seeing on
the Webcast is more truly reflective of Sam. He has a mischievous
side, playful, yet extremely inquisitive.''
</P>
<P>
   And what of the line between entertainment and journalism? Jones
does not see a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ''Entertainment to me is a program that has a single, often
diversionary goal,'' he says. ''What Sam Donaldson does is not
escapist entertainment. It's the presentation of information but in
an engaging way.''
</P>
<P>
   As one of the first news veterans with a regular Internet show,
Donaldson is a pioneer. He initially hesitated, he says, but then
recognized that at age 66 he was unlikely to succeed Peter Jennings
as the evening news anchor. Donaldson believes others will join him
''once they see it is the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Viewership for the Net show remains in the thousands rather than
the millions typical for network TV. Yet Donaldson says he and his
network are committed to it. ''This is a major effort. Why would a
company do this just to put me out to pasture?''
</P>
<P>
   Jones says ABC cares more at this point about understanding the
new medium than about making money. Begun in September, the
20-minute program includes one commercial break -- Donaldson jokes
that it costs $3.25 a spot.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson's early Web shows took more of a hard-news approach.
But when the show booked politicians, viewership dropped. And few
bothered to watch Ernest Hemingway's son, even though Donaldson
considered the segment ''smashing.''
</P>
<P>
   The main lesson so far: Although it's a television program
broadcast over the Net, don't make it appear too much like one.
Adapt the program to the online audience.
</P>
<P>
   ''They want to know about Metallica's suit against Napster far
more than they want to know about George W. Bush's plan for foreign
policy,'' Donaldson says.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the show emphasizes high-tech guests and topics, as well as
such pop icons as Ullman and Garofalo. To keep shows relevant to
Web users who may watch them days or weeks later, the show no
longer recaps top stories.
</P>
<P>
   Usually produced live, it lets viewers participate through
informal surveys, e-mail, chat and discussion boards. Donaldson
personally answers some of the messages and reads audience
questions on the show. The show fits in a 2-inch computer window,
with jerky, grainy video.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, it looks and feels like ''This Week'' and other news
programs on television -- an approach some industry insiders
question.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Brown, editor in chief of MSNBC.com, believes that
merely bringing TV to the Internet is like showing newspapers on
TV.
</P>
<P>
   But Donaldson believes Web viewers will watch a TV-like show
that is compelling. That is where his looser format comes in.
</P>
<P>
   On the Sports Illustrated segment, he flipped through the
swimsuit issue. He asked pointed questions about whether the
magazine promotes sexism, but also joked with a female producer,
''Where's your swimsuit, Vanessa?'' He inquired about President
Clinton's magazine subscriptions through White House reporter Josh
Gerstein.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson says he may have gone too far with the swimsuits;
although that segment was one of the most-watched, he concedes
viewers were ''there for the cheesecake.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We're trying to get a larger audience, but not at any price,
not in any way,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://abcnews.go.com
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in television ....
</P>
<P>
   '20/20': Most Americans readily accept that alcoholism is a
''disease'' whose only treatment is abstinence. But now those views
are being challenged and the means of treatment questioned. ABC
News medical correspondent Dr. Nancy Snyderman examines the
conventional theories about drinking, opening the door on a heated
debate in the medical and treatment communities. This special
edition of ''20/20'' looks at bold new ways to approach the problem
and calls for a re-examination of long-accepted views. It airs
Wednesday at 10 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
