<HEADLINE> Dow Down 69; Nasdaq Up 20  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Market averages were mixed today as investors
searched for direction in a quiet market. Continued interest in
technology stocks helped the Nasdaq stay in positive territory for
a fourth straight session.
</P>
<P>
   In morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 68.94 at 10,746.36.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Nasdaq composite index
was up 19.94 to 3,841.70, but the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
down 2.86 to 1,464.77.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said investors appeared to be regrouping after sharp
gains last week. The Nasdaq, which had been battered in March and
April, soared a record-breaking 19 percent last week as investors
flocked back to the technology stock that dominate its ranks. The
Dow, which hadn't suffered as badly, rose 4.8 percent last week.
</P>
<P>
   ''The market's doing extremely well after last week's screamer,
which set us up for a little profit-taking,'' said Ralph Bloch,
chief market analyst at Raymond James &AMP; Associates in St.
Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while some investors were indeed cashing in stocks to
capture gains, more stocks were rising than falling in the overall
market.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's some good underlying strength,'' Bloch said. ''That's
the sign of a market engaging in a healthy pause.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel fell 31.25 cents to $132.25. The company said it will
delay the launch of its integrated processor, code-named Timna,
because of a conflict with standard memory. The processor, which
was expected to debut in the second half of this year, has now been
delayed until the first quarter of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But a broad range of technology stocks advanced today. Qualcomm
rose $1.375 to $68.625 and PMC-Sierra rose $3.219 to $190.348.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the Nasdaq, Starbucks rose $2.50 to $38.125. The coffee
company will be added to the Staandard &AMP; Poor's 500 on Wednesday,
prompting many index-fund managers to buy the stock so that their
portfolios will continue to mirror the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan fell $4.125 to $133, contributing most to the Dow's
decline.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 307.44 million
shares, ahead of Monday's sluggish pace.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq, four stocks rose for every three that fell.
</P>
<P>
   Trading volume remained fairly low as investors opted to wait
for more information on the strength of the U.S. economy before
taking significant new positions. The next potentially
market-moving report will reach traders on Friday, when the Labor
Department releases the Producer Price Index.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 6.21 to 519.51.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
