<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egan meets with mediator to try to settle sexual abuse cases  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- New York Archbishop-elect Edward Egan
met with a federal magistrate to try to settle more than 20
lawsuits filed against the Roman Catholic Diocese of Bridgeport by
people who claim they were molested by priests, the Connecticut
Post reported.
</P>
<P>
   Egan was seen meeting Monday with U.S. Magistrate William I.
Garfinkle, the newspaper said Tuesday, citing sources it did not
identify.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the diocese confirmed that Egan agreed to meet
with Garfinkle in the hope of settling the suits, the Post said.
Lawyers for both the diocese and the plaintiffs had picked
Garfinkle as a mediator some time earlier, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Drohan, a spokesman for the diocese, told The Associated
Press on Tuesday that he could not comment. Cindy Robinson, a
lawyer whose firm has brought most of the lawsuits, also declined
to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Egan was named archbishop of New York on May 11, a week after
the death of Cardinal John O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   In lawsuits filed against the diocese, 23 people claim they were
sexually assaulted by six current and former priests in the
Bridgeport diocese.
</P>
<P>
   According to the lawsuits, the alleged sexual assaults date back
to the late 1960s, when the plaintiffs were either altar boys or
members of diocesan youth organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Egan did not become bishop of the Bridgeport diocese until 1988.
The lawsuits claim he knew about the incidents when he took office
but took action to keep them secret.
</P>
<P>
   The diocese has repeatedly denied that Egan tried to cover up
alleged abuse by priests.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not true. As soon as allegations were made ... he took
immediate action,'' Drohan said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits are currently pending in Waterbury Superior Court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
