<DOCNO> APW20000606.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Land Declared Toad Habitat  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nearly 500,000 acres in Southern California,
scattered from San Diego to Monterey, will be declared critical
habitat for the endangered Southwestern arroyo toad, potentially
limiting development in some areas, federal officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The action, expected to be formally announced Thursday, is the
result of consent agreement involving a lawsuit by several
environmental groups, who accused the Interior Department of
violating the Endangered Species Act by not promptly making habitat
designations.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the U.S. Fish And Wildlife Service is expected to make
dozens of new habitat designations to protect rare species this
year because of pressure from the courts.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the plan to protect the arroyo toad, the Fish and
Wildlife Service will declare 478,400 California acres as critical
habitat for the species. About half of the acres are private land
and the rest managed by federal, state or local governments,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The three-inch long arroyo toad, which once could be found
throughout the Southern and Central California watersheds, breeds
in slow-flowing rivers and shallow, gravelly pools. It's range now
is believed limited to 22 drainage areas with an estimated 75
percent of its original area of habitat having been eliminated by
dam construction, urbanization and human activities, according to
the National Wildlife Federation.
</P>
<P>
   The critical habitat designation by the Fish and Wildlife
Service will include portions of Monterey, Santa Barbara, Ventura,
Los Angeles, San Bernardino, Orange, Riverside and San Diego
counties, including lands within four national forests, according
to agency officials, who spoke on condition of not being further
identified.
</P>
<P>
   The designation does not establish a special preserve or refuge
for the species and in most cases will not directly affect how
property owners use private land unless an action involves federal
money or a federal permit, officials said. However, some developers
might be affected when they seek federal wetland permits, for
example.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the land singled out for protection of the arroyo toad
already is designated critical habitat for another endangered
species, the California gnatcatcher. The critical habitat
designation does not include lands that are part of a formal
Habitat Conservation Plan that under agreement with the government
already requires certain management programs aimed at protecting
rare species.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny gray toad was put on the endangered list in 1994 under
the federal Endangered Species Act, which requires that the
government promptly designate what habitat is needed for the
species survival. When the Interior Department failed for years to
make such a designation, the Center for Biological Diversity, based
in Tucson, Ariz., filed a lawsuit in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Fish and Wildlife Service agreed in federal court
in San Francisco in response to the lawsuit to make a critical
habitat designation. The court set a June 1, 2000 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   For an area to be designated critical habitat it must be
determined by biologists to be essential for the conservation of a
threatened or endangered species, although the species does not
necessarily have to be found on the land. Once a designation is
made, special land management is required to protect the species,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   However, officials also emphasized that not all the land within
a designated habitat boundary will require special management. For
example existing roads, shopping areas and other populated areas
within the boundary are not expected to serve as habitat for the
toad, so would require no special consultation with the Fish and
Wildlife Service.
</P>
<P>
   Some details of the planned designation were first reported
Tuesday by the Los Angeles Times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-06-00 1314 </TRAILER>
