<HEADLINE> Dow Down 42; Nasdaq Up 53  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Market averages were mixed today as investors
searched for direction in a quiet market. Continued interest in
technology stocks helped the Nasdaq stay in positive territory for
a fourth straight session.
</P>
<P>
   In early afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 41.78 at 10,773.52.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were faring better. The Nasdaq
composite index was up 52.59 to 3,874.35, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was down 1.49 to 1,469.12.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said investors appeared to be regrouping after sharp
gains last week. The Nasdaq, which had been battered in March and
April, soared a record-breaking 19 percent last week as investors
flocked back to the technology stock that dominate its ranks. The
Dow, which hadn't suffered as badly, rose 4.8 percent last week.
</P>
<P>
   ''The market's doing extremely well after last week's screamer,
which set us up for a little profit-taking,'' said Ralph Bloch,
chief market analyst at Raymond James &AMP; Associates in St.
Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while some investors were indeed cashing in stocks to
capture gains, more stocks were rising than falling in the overall
market.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's some good underlying strength,'' Bloch said. ''That's
the sign of a market engaging in a healthy pause.''
</P>
<P>
   Stocks that fell prey to profit-takers included Sun
Microsystems, down $1.563 to $86.625.
</P>
<P>
   But a broad range of technology stocks advanced today. Qualcomm
rose $4.313 to $71.563 and PMC-Sierra rose $3.766 to $190.891.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the Nasdaq, Starbucks rose $2.625 to $38.25. The coffee
company will be added to the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 on Wednesday,
prompting many index-fund managers to buy the stock so that their
portfolios will continue to mirror the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan fell $4.625 to $132.50 contributing most to the
Dow's decline. Merrill Lynch analyst Judah Kraushaar told clients
that periods of rising interest rates have typically been bad for
investment banking revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Also, shares of many prominent retailers fell today as investors
reasoned that signs of a slowdown in consumer spending could mean
that retailers will see revenue and profits slide. Circuit City
plunged $12 to $40.125 after saying that sales were flat in May.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Circuit City's warning convinced investors that
other retailers will also struggle in the coming months. Wal-Mart
fell $1.313 to $58.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 7-to-6 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 632.85 million
shares, ahead of Monday's sluggish pace.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq, five stocks rose for every four that fell.
</P>
<P>
   Trading volume remained fairly low as investors opted to wait
for more information on the strength of the U.S. economy before
taking significant new positions. The next potentially
market-moving report will reach traders on Friday, when the Labor
Department releases the Producer Price Index.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 8.54 to 521.84.
</P>
