<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Washington Opera May Be Renamed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Washington Opera, headed by Artistic
Director Placido Domingo, will soon be officially known as the
National Opera, if the House has its way.
</P>
<P>
   The House cast a voice vote Tuesday to rename the 44-year-old
opera company, and it would join the National Symphony Orchestra,
which also performs out of the Kennedy Center, with the national
designation.
</P>
<P>
   Bill sponsor Rep. William Goodling, R-Pa., said the opera
company ''has achieved the stature of a world-class company'' and
the new name would give it national prominence, increase ticket
sales and improve fund-raising prospects.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Opera has earned a position of leadership in the
musical world without the government support typical in most world
capitals, he said. The new designation, which must still be
approved by the Senate, would not bring federal funding or
subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe the National Opera will set an example for the
country and will welcome millions who would otherwise not be
inclined to attend the opera,'' said Eleanor Holmes Norton, the
Democratic delegate from the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Opera requested congressional approval of the new
name even though, as a private company, it doesn't need such
legislation to make the switch, Goodling said. However, his office
said the federal designation would give the company an important
boost in prestige.
</P>
<P>
   The opera, founded in 1956 by Day Thorpe, music critic for the
now defunct Washington Star newspaper, has become one of the
nation's most successful and prolific.
</P>
<P>
   It has 80 performances in the 2000-2001 season and earns 65
percent of its budget through ticket sales, with the remaining 35
percent coming from contributions. The ticket sale-to-contribution
ratio is the highest of any opera company in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The House on Tuesday also took up resolutions praising the
United States Philharmonic Society and recognizing the importance
of African-American music to global culture.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill number is H.R. 4542.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The opera site: http://www.dc-opera.org/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-06-00 1432 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000606.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strong Quake Shakes Turkey; 3 Dead  </HEADLINE>
By SELCAN HACAOGLU
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORTA, Turkey (AP) -- A strong earthquake struck rural central
Turkey on Tuesday, collapsing homes and killing two people,
including a beekeeper crushed to death by falling stones as he
slept.
</P>
<P>
   Eight people were injured in villages just north of Turkey's
capital, Ankara. The magnitude 5.9 quake destroyed or damaged some
4,000 homes.
</P>
<P>
   The quake was centered on Cerkes, a town in the green hills 60
miles north of Ankara, in Cankiri province.
</P>
<P>
   Cankiri lies close to the North Anatolian Fault, the source of
two strong earthquakes that leveled parts of northwestern Turkey in
August and November, killing more than 18,000 people and destroying
thousands of buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue teams rushing to the area had to zigzag through roads
that were blocked by huge rocks that tumbled from the hillsides.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, rain began to fall, further hampering rescue
efforts and frustrating workers trying to set up tents for those
made homeless.
</P>
<P>
   The quake startled residents of Ankara and was strong enough to
cause hairline cracks in the parliament building, in some rooms
from floor to ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   In the village of Orta Karga, beekeeper Ahmet Arslan was crushed
when the roof and a wall of his home collapsed onto his bed after
the quake struck shortly after dawn.
</P>
<P>
   ''The stones ... covered his body like a grave,'' said Huseyin
Bayram, a neighbor who dug out Arslan's body.
</P>
<P>
   At least 30 people were injured in the town of Orta and its
surrounding villages, which include Orta Karga. Most of those
injured were hit by bricks or collapsed chimneys, said Mehmet Ali
Yaman, a doctor who treated the injured.
</P>
<P>
   ''We shook so hard, I threw myself out of the window,'' said
Ramazan Aydin, who injured his back in the fall. ''I panicked so
much I didn't know what I was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Villagers said that the death toll might have been higher, but
many people were either awake and out of their homes at morning
Islamic prayers or in the fields tending their sheep.
</P>
<P>
   The quake damaged electricity and telephone lines in the area.
</P>
<P>
   In Yuva, the village fountain was spewing mud-colored water
after the quake.
</P>
<P>
   In Cubuk, just outside of the capital of Ankara, a 17-year-old
boy was killed when a three-story building collapsed, said the
town's mayor, Mustafa Gokmen. The boy's brother was pulled from the
debris injured but alive, and three other members of the family
were also injured. At least 14 other people were also injured in
the town.
</P>
<P>
   The semiofficial Anatolia news agency reported early Tuesday
that one person died after jumping from a building, but later said
that person had survived with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thankfully, the number of lives lost is very low,'' Prime
Minister Bulent Ecevit said in Oslo. He decided against cutting
short his visit to Norway.
</P>
<P>
   The government, severely criticized for its slow response during
the two earlier quakes, was better organized this time. It moved
quickly to send helicopters to assess the damage, set up crisis
centers to coordinate rescue operations and dispatched mobile
kitchens, medical centers, blankets and tents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
