<HEADLINE> Serbs Clash With NATO Peacekeepers  </HEADLINE>
By DANICA KIRKA
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRACANICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Serbs angry over a grenade attack
swarmed around a British general Tuesday, prompting his bodyguards
to fire into the crowd, escalating tension in a community
increasingly restive over NATO's inability to protect it. One
person was injured.
</P>
<P>
   The outrage in this Serb enclave comes after a surge of attacks
Kosovo's Serb community claims are intended to drive them and other
minorities from the province. Eight people have died in the past
week, and many Serbs say peacekeepers have failed to ensure their
safety.
</P>
<P>
   A Serb delegation plans to travel Wednesday to U.N. headquarters
in New York to demand self-rule for Serbs in Kosovo and better
security, according to the independent Yugoslav news agency FoNet.
</P>
<P>
   The troubles in this monastery town just south of the capital,
Pristina, escalated quickly Tuesday. At midmorning, an attacker
drove alongside the market in the center of town and hurled a
grenade, witnesses and NATO-led peacekeepers said.
</P>
<P>
   Furious that NATO troops did not prevent the attack, a crowd
gathered and began to stone Swedish peacekeepers who form a huge
share of the contingent stationed in the town.
</P>
<P>
   The mob pulled people out of cars, beat them and set the
vehicles on fire. Drivers and others, reportedly ethnic Albanians,
retreated to the town's 14th century Serbian Orthodox monastery for
refuge.
</P>
<P>
   The commander of the British sector, Brig. Richard Shirreff
rushed to the scene to calm the crowd of several hundred. The mob
closed around him and took the weapon of one of his bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   Others in his security detail fired shots into the air and one
into the crowd, injuring one person, NATO officials said. NATO-led
peacekeepers originally reported three people were injured, but
later revised the figure downward.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were attacked,'' Shirreff said. ''We had to fire shots to
protect ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Local Serbs stood outside the monastery throughout the day,
watching cars, trucks and vans smolder. They called out to
reporters to express their outrage over the grenade attack.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was thrown right in front of KFOR,'' said Dragan
Stojanovic, 48, using the acronym for the NATO peacekeepers' Kosovo
Force. ''How come they weren't able to stop that car? Aren't they
ashamed?''
</P>
<P>
   The local Serb National Council condemned the grenade attack,
claiming it was only the latest act from a ''wave of organized
Albanian terrorist groups seeking to expel Serbs from Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We have repeatedly told KFOR that the market in Gracanica is a
dangerous site ... but NATO found no solutions for the problem,''
Father Sava Janjic told Yugoslavia's private Beta news agency.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the medical center in Gracanica, Zorica Nedeljkovic,
told Beta that a total of 12 Serbs were injured -- eight in the
grenade attack and four in the subsequent clash with NATO-led
peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   The melee comes at a sensitive political moment for the
province's Serbs, just days before the anniversary of the arrival
of NATO-led peacekeepers, who took over Kosovo after a 78-day air
war to end Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's repression of
ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   As the date of the anniversary has drawn closer, moderate Serbs
have grown more impatient with their increasing isolation in
Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-06-00 1450 </TRAILER>
