<HEADLINE> China Official To Visit Yugoslavia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A top Chinese official will visit
Yugoslavia next week in a sign of support for embattled President
Slobodan Milosevic's government.
</P>
<P>
   Li Peng, the speaker of China's parliament and second-ranking
member of the ruling Communist Party, will make the official visit
June 11-13, according to a statement from Yugoslav authorities that
was carried by the official Tanjug news agency.
</P>
<P>
   Li will address the Yugoslav parliament during a session on June
12, Beta news agency reported
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear whether the Chinese lawmaker will meet
Milosevic, who has been politically isolated by the United States
and its allies and indicted by the United Nations war crimes
tribunal in The Hague, Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   China is one of the few countries maintaining ties with
Milosevic's government following last year's NATO bombing of the
country. Milosevic visited China in November 1997.
</P>
<P>
   China opposed the NATO bombing that included a mistaken hit on
the Chinese embassy in Belgrade that killed three Chinese citizens.
The incident led to tensions in U.S.-China relations.
</P>
<P>
   Tanjug said Li's meetings with Yugoslav officials will focus on
relations between the two countries and international issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
