<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Louima grilled about civil suit  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HAYS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Taking his familiar spot on the witness stand,
Abner Louima told a jury Tuesday that he was suing the police
officer sitting at the defense table even though the officer was
not among those who tortured him in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, Francisco Rosario, is on trial in Brooklyn federal
court for allegedly lying to FBI agents investigating the notorious
assault in a precinct bathroom. Louima also has named Rosario -
along with several other officers, the city and the police
department - in a lawsuit seeking $155 million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   ''Do you believe that it will help your civil case if Officer
Rosario is convicted here?'' Rosario's attorney, Richard Levitt,
asked Louima.
</P>
<P>
   ''That, I don't know,'' Louima replied.
</P>
<P>
   The cross-examination on the trial's second day sought to
portray Louima as a professional victim eager to tailor his
testimony to the needs both of criminal prosecutors and his own
civil suit. Federal authorities are giving him $2,000 a month for
living expenses while he recovers from the attack and serves as
their star witness.
</P>
<P>
   Louima's suit, filed in 1998, claims that officers at Brooklyn's
70th Precinct conspired to create a ''blue wall of silence and lies
to obstruct justice.'' It also charges police and union officials
with condoning an ''environment in which the most violent police
officers believed they would be insulated'' from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   In three criminal trials, including Rosario's, Louima has
testified about an ordeal stemming from his arrest in a street
brawl outside a Brooklyn nightclub on Aug. 9, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The prisoner was handcuffed and taken to the precinct. There,
Officer Justin Volpe - mistakenly believing Louima had punched him
- sought revenge by sodomizing the prisoner with a broken
broomstick and threatening to kill him if he reported it.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe, who pleaded guilty, is serving 30 years. A jury convicted
a second patrolman, Charles Schwarz, of pinning Louima down during
the assault; he and former officers Thomas Bruder and Thomas Wiese
were later convicted of conspiring to conceal Schwarz's role in the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Rosario, 35, and his partner - both roving plainclothes officers
- happened to be filling out paperwork in a holding cell area when
Volpe threw a battered Louima, his pants still down, into a cell
following the assault, authorities said. Prosecutors allege the
partners conspired to lie to FBI agents as part of a cover-up -
first by saying they were never there, then by claiming Louima's
escort was not Volpe.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt admitted Monday in opening statements that Rosario at
first tried to mislead authorities to protect himself - a mistake,
he argued, that does not rise to a federal offense.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer also said his client honestly believed another
officer had put Louima in the holding cell. He noted that other
witnesses, including Louima, had given conflicting statements about
the identity of the officer.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Levitt confronted Louima with state grand jury
testimony in which he indicated Schwarz had put him in the cell.
Several months later, while in front of a federal grand jury,
Louima changed the story to make that officer Volpe.
</P>
<P>
   Louima admitted meeting with federal authorities behind closed
doors at least 10 times between the two grand juries. But he
insisted his testimony was based on memory, not coaching.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-06-00 1518 </TRAILER>
