<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 42; Nasdaq Down 18  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned mostly lower today as investors
took some profits after three consecutive strong sessions. Banking
and retail stocks fell as investors realized that an economic
slowdown may keep inflation at bay, but will also hurt certain
business sectors.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the Dow
Jones industrial average was down 41.78 at 10,773.52.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also lower, having given up early
gains. The Nasdaq composite index was down 18.11 to 3,803.65, and
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 8.20 to 1,459.43.
</P>
<P>
   For the past three sessions, stocks have risen on investors'
hopes that the economy has slowed enough to persuade the Federal
Reserve to stop raising interest rates. But today, investors
changed tacks, selling stocks that are seen as vulnerable to
economic slowdowns.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan fell $4.125 to $133, contributing most to the Dow's
decline. Merrill Lynch analyst Judah Kraushaar told clients that
periods of rising interest rates have typically been bad for
investment banking revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Also, shares of many prominent retailers fell as investors
reasoned that signs of a slowdown in consumer spending could mean
retailers will see revenue and profits slide. Circuit City plunged
$12.688 to $39.438 after saying that sales were flat in May.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Circuit City's warning convinced investors that
other retailers will also struggle in the coming months. Wal-Mart
fell $1.313 to $58.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, analysts said investors appeared to be
regrouping after sharp gains last week. The Nasdaq, which had been
battered in March and April, soared a record-breaking 19 percent
last week as investors flocked back to the technology stock that
dominate its ranks. The Dow, which hadn't suffered as badly, rose
4.8 percent last week.
</P>
<P>
   ''The market's doing extremely well after last week's screamer,
which set us up for a little profit-taking,'' said Ralph Bloch,
chief market analyst at Raymond James &AMP; Associates in St.
Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while some investors were indeed cashing in stocks to
capture gains, more stocks were rising than falling in the overall
market.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's some good underlying strength,'' Bloch said. ''That's
the sign of a market engaging in a healthy pause.''
</P>
<P>
   Stocks that fell prey to profit-takers included Sun
Microsystems, down $2.813 to $85.375.
</P>
<P>
   But a broad range of technology stocks advanced today. Qualcomm
rose $2.125 to $69.375 and PMC-Sierra rose $3.766 to $190.891.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the Nasdaq, Starbucks rose $1.938 to $37.563. The coffee
company will be added to the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 on Wednesday,
prompting many index-fund managers to buy the stock so that their
portfolios will continue to mirror the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 7-to-6 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 749.32 million
shares, ahead of Monday's sluggish pace.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq, 10 stocks rose for every nine that fell.
</P>
<P>
   Trading volume remained fairly low as investors opted to wait
for more information on the strength of the U.S. economy before
taking significant new positions. The next potentially
market-moving report will reach traders on Friday, when the Labor
Department releases the Producer Price Index.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 2.79 to 516.09.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
