<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Raises on tap for governor and other elected officials  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - The salary for governor's office will
nearly double in 2003, and other elected officials will get raises
next year.
</P>
<P>
   The pay raise boosts the governor's salary from $78,000 to
$150,000 - the first increase for the office since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John G. Rowland, whose current term expires in 2002, signed
the pay raise bill last Thursday. Unlike other bill signings, no
notice was given to reporters that Rowland had signed the bill.
Officials from Rowland's office called that an unintentional
oversight, and said the information was posted on the Internet
Friday and made available outside the governor's press secretary's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the raises by reporters Tuesday, Rowland brushed off
reports that the increase would make Connecticut's governor one of
the highest-paid state leaders in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've seen comparisons,'' Rowland said. ''But that's not true -
not when you compare it to what the other salaries are going to be
two more years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   New York Gov. George Pataki and California Gov. Gray Davis
currently top the list of highest-paid governors.
</P>
<P>
   The Citizens Compensation Commission, which sets salary levels
for elected officials in California, in March approved an increase
to the governor's salary to $175,000 a year, effective in December.
Davis has said he will decline the increase.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut increase passed without debate last month,
winning approval in the House of Representatives 97-53, and in the
Senate 20-15, in the waning hours of the 2000 legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also boosts the salaries of the lieutenant governor,
secretary of the state, attorney general and treasurer, which were
last raised in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Rank-and-file members of the state's part-time General Assembly
- who voted themselves a $5,100 raise in 1998 - are getting another
increase. Their $21,788 salaries are climbing to $28,000 in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to their salaries, House members receive $4,500 a
year in travel expenses. Senators get $5,500.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Andrew Roraback, R-Goshen, voted against the raises.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we could have voted just on the governor's salary, I would
have voted 'yes' in a heartbeat,'' he said. ''But only two years
have passed since the legislative raises, and the magnitude of the
new raise is large.''
</P>
<P>
   The salaries of the Senate president pro tempore and House
speaker will be raised from $30,108 to $38,689. Minority leaders
will get $8,000 raises.
</P>
<P>
   Judges' salaries also going up. The Supreme Court chief
justice's pay would be raised in 2002 from $140,582 to $149,582,
and the chief court administrator's salary will be boosted from
$134,738 to $143,738.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court judges will make $125,000 in 2002, $9,000 more
than they will earn in 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
