<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> It's a drive-by attack on Pirro's auto deductions  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) - A couple of Ferraris, a couple of
Mercedes Benzes, a Bentley and several sport utility vehicles
tooled through the testimony of an Internal Revenue Service agent
Tuesday at the tax evasion trial of Albert Pirro, husband of the
Westchester district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   In general, said agent John Dennehy, the cars were for the
Pirros' personal pleasure, not for business, and should not have
been used to generate tens of thousands of dollars in tax
deductions for Pirro's companies.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro and his brother Anthony are accused of disguising more
than $1 million in such personal expenses as business write-offs.
The 3-week-old trial has provided a glimpse at the lavish lifestyle
of the district attorney and her husband, which prosecutors say was
partially supported with cash that should have gone to the
government. Jeanine Pirro is not charged.
</P>
<P>
   Dennehy, prompted by Assistant U.S. Attorney Cathy Seibel,
listed vehicle after vehicle, noting how each was used as a
business expense and the reasons he concluded that the deductions
should be disallowed.
</P>
<P>
   He said he gave Pirro the benefit of any doubt, allowing all
deductions for any vehicle that he could not prove was entirely for
personal use.
</P>
<P>
   But that left plenty, he said:
</P>
<P>
   -A 1984 Ferrari, listed on an insurance document as for Albert
Pirro's personal use, was deducted by his law firm for loan
payments and depreciation.
</P>
<P>
   -The 1989 Mercedes that carried Jeanine Pirro's judicial license
plates had its lease payments deducted by the Ferris-Pirro
Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   -A 1990 Toyota 4Runner that was shipped to Florida - where the
Pirros have a vacation home - was written off for car payments and
depreciation by the law firm.
</P>
<P>
   -A 1992 Mercedes driven by Jeanine Pirro's mother and serviced
near her home in Elmira was ''accounted for as if a company car''
by Distinctive Properties of Yonkers.
</P>
<P>
   -A 1994 Ford Explorer should have been added to Albert Pirro's
income that year, but instead was treated as a company asset by the
law firm, which deducted interest payments and depreciation.
</P>
<P>
   -Similarly, the $123,000 cost of a 1995 Ferrari purchased by the
law firm should have been added to Pirro's income, since it was for
his personal use and was sent down to Florida. Instead, the law
firm took the deductions and Pirro did not report the income.
</P>
<P>
   Other vehicles mentioned included the Bentley, a Chevrolet
Tahoe, a Jeep Cherokee and a Ford Bronco.
</P>
<P>
   The 1989 Mercedes came in for special scrutiny, including a
computerized slide show that showed seven different companies
involved in the financing. Prosecutors said in pretrial papers that
the financing was ''an empty financial transaction, a sham'' used
by Albert Pirro to mask fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro has emphasized that when he learned of the tax
investigation, he had his tax returns redone and paid back nearly
$1 million in back taxes and interest. Judge Barrington Parker
reminded the jury Tuesday that for a criminal conviction, the
government must prove there was ''intent to evade a substantial
amount of taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennehy may have been addressing that when he testified that in
examining the records of Anthony Pirro, who was Albert Pirro's
accountant, he saw that in 1992 deductions were reduced by $40,000
because they were personal; in 1994, by contrast, all expenses
listed as ''personal'' in Anthony Pirro's ledger were nevertheless
deducted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-06-00 1603 </TRAILER>
