<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Small Party Exits Poland Coalition  </HEADLINE>
By ANDRZEJ STYLINSKI
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- A small liberal party dropped out of its
2{-year-old coalition with Poland's fractious Solidarity bloc on
Tuesday, frustrated over the government's failure to push through
key reforms needed to get Poland into the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   After the Freedom Union's move, the Solidarity's political
leaders will try to run a government without a majority in
parliament, raising the possibility of early elections.
</P>
<P>
   Solidarity ''is taking full responsibility for governing
Poland,'' the bloc's political chief, Marian Krzaklewski, said
after a leadership meeting.
</P>
<P>
   He said Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek would soon nominate
candidates to replace the Union's five departing Cabinet ministers.
</P>
<P>
   The breakup followed an announcement by Freedom Union leader
Leszek Balcerowicz, who also is finance minister, that his party
was abandoning efforts to salvage the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Buzek, 59, remains the longest serving prime minister in the
tumultuous transition years since Poland toppled communist rule in
1989.
</P>
<P>
   But it is unclear how Solidarity will fare without a majority in
the already contentious parliament. Its leaders are hoping to avoid
early elections because polls suggest they would be won by the
Democratic Left Alliance, a coalition of former communists.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their chronic feuding, the coalition partners had
managed to carry out broad reforms in social security and health
care and to accelerate the restructuring of ailing communist-area
industries. They also launched EU membership talks and presided
over Poland's landmark entry into NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Work on key legislation has stalled in recent months, however,
and the two sides finally fell out over disagreement on who should
replace Buzek, whom the Union blamed for not rallying Solidarity
legislators behind reform measures demanded by the EU.
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom Union ordered its ministers to resign from the
Cabinet two weeks ago, but they had agreed to continue working
while party leaders struggled to negotiate a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Solidarity proposed Krzaklewski as Buzek's replacement.
</P>
<P>
   But the Freedom Union contended he would be no more effective
than Buzek and would be distracted by his plans for a long-shot run
for the presidency this fall against incumbent Aleksander
Kwasniewski, an ex-communist who has become Poland's most popular
politician.
</P>
<P>
   ''The negotiations were leading nowhere. Our partners had no
intention to reach agreement,'' said Freedom Union spokesman
Andrzej Potocki.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government can count on our support wherever it will
continue our joint efforts,'' Potocki said. ''We will not destroy
the government for the fun of being in opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Boguslaw Grabowski, a central bank economist who was briefly
considered as a possible Buzek replacement, said Solidarity faced a
''very difficult task'' and a test of its commitment to economic
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he saw no threat to Poland's economy, the most
successful in the former Soviet bloc, or to billions of dollars of
investment poured in by Western firms, especially from Germany and
the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
