<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon Changes Korea Death Toll  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon has revised yet again its count
of Americans who died in the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   Although the latest tally from the report, Service and
Casualties in Major Wars and Conflicts, put the total at 36,913,
the Pentagon said Tuesday that revisions made last week changed it
to 36,516.
</P>
<P>
   The main change: 432 deaths that had been in the ''non-battle''
category for Korean War losses -- meaning troops lost to accidents,
illness and other non-combat causes -- were shifted to a separate
category of U.S. military deaths that occurred elsewhere in the
world during the three-year war.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said there were 2,830 ''non-battle'' deaths in
Korea, not the 3,262 it had reported previously. It also increased
the number of combat deaths in Korea by 35, to 33,686. This number
has changed many times over the years, but only slightly. In 1974,
for example, it stood at 33,629.
</P>
<P>
   The war, in which U.S. and United Nations forces fought on the
side of South Korea against communist North Korea and its Chinese
and Soviet allies, began June 25, 1950, and ended in a truce July
27, 1953.
</P>
<P>
   In a related development, the Pentagon said a U.S. government
delegation will open negotiations with North Korea on Wednesday on
recovering remains of American servicemen who were lost in battle
in North Korea during the war. Slightly more than 8,100 U.S.
servicemen are unaccounted for from the war.
</P>
<P>
   The talks, to be held in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, are to last for
three days, spokesman Larry Greer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-06-00 1605 </TRAILER>
