<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State law part of drive to save newborns from abandonment  </HEADLINE>
By SUSANNE YOUMANS
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Meriden Police Chief Robert E. Kosienski
wishes a state law allowing mothers to give up their newborns at a
hospital emergency room - no questions asked - had come 12 years
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe then, he said Tuesday, one young woman might not have left
her 71/2-pound, blue-eyed baby boy in a parking lot to freeze to
death.
</P>
<P>
   ''If David Paul's mother had known about the law, there's a good
chance she may have taken advantage of it,'' Kosienski said of the
child, who police named after he was found. ''There's that window
to save the baby's life.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John G. Rowland last week signed the law to create ''safe
havens'' for newborns at risk of abandonment, a measure supporters
say gives scared young mothers a new option and saves babies'
lives. It takes effect Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   At least 28 states have either adopted or are considering
similar legislation this year alone, according to the National
Conference of State Legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   Under Connecticut's law, passed by the Legislature unanimously,
parents can leave a baby under 31 days old at the emergency room of
any hospital in the state. The parent will receive an
identification number and has 30 days to ask the court to be
reunited with the child. Otherwise, parental rights will be
terminated and the adoption process begun.
</P>
<P>
   If the baby has not been abused, the mother cannot be
prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   ''Frequently we have babies having babies ... and they panic,''
said state Rep. Ann Dandrow, R-Southington, who sponsored the
legislation. ''If they knew of other options, they would take
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials cannot say how many newborns are abandoned every year.
The U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, compiling figures
from media reports, said there were reports of 105 infants
abandoned in ''public places'' in 1998, including 33 who were dead.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, the only other recent year for which figures were
compiled, there were 65 infants abandoned in public places - eight
of them dead.
</P>
<P>
   According to the NCSL, states that have approved or considered
infant abandonment legislation this year include California,
Florida, New York and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   But some child welfare advocates say the programs are likely to
do little for the women targeted.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most of our girls are not going to walk into a hospital, where
there are security guards and cameras, to drop off a baby,'' said
Angel Waters, of Project Cuddle, a Costa Mesa, Calif.-based
organization which operates a 24-hour hot line to prevent
abandonment.
</P>
<P>
   James Dinnan, who prosecuted the 1995 case of a 16-year-old
Cheshire girl who gave birth at home and threw the baby in the
trash, said she and women like her probably would not seek the help
the law allows. Amanda Beckett, who was convicted of second-degree
manslaughter and served seven months in prison, never told anyone
she was pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   ''When these people become pregnant, it's too late,'' said
Dinnan, now a senior assistant state's attorney in Meriden.
</P>
<P>
   Other critics say the programs ensure no support for the women,
ignore the role of the father and may actually encourage women to
abandon a baby if they are unhappy with its sex or if it has
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say that if just one mother takes advantage of the
program, that's one less newborn dead and one less woman sent to
jail.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some critics say 'wait and see how it's working elsewhere,''
said Jodi Brooks, a television news reporter in Mobile, Ala., who
founded a program in her community in 1998. ''Every time we wait,
there's a chance of losing another life.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the program for infants less than three days old began in
Mobile, one baby has been rescued from a trash pile, another two
have been turned in at hospitals, and two teen-age girls have
received counseling that guided them through successful
pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks said some programs suffer because the legislation leaves
unexpected holes.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut Hospital Association has already asked state
officials for guidance on some questions unanswered in the law,
said spokeswoman Carrie Brady. The questions include how to handle
babies who appear to be more than 31 days old and how to determine
whether the person giving up the child has the mother's permission
to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ''We support it in principle, but there are some implementation
issues,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   For information on Connecticut's law -http://www.cga.state.ct.us
</P>
<P>
   Project Cuddle -http://www.projectcuddle.org
</P>
<P>
   Mobile, Ala.'s program-http://www.secretsafeplace.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-06-00 1626 </TRAILER>
