<HEADLINE> Elian Gets Big Network TV Coverage  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The network evening news shows have devoted
more stories to Elian Gonzalez than to any other nonelection story
since the O.J. Simpson case, according to a study by the Center for
Media and Public Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   During comparable time periods, coverage of the 6-year-old
shipwreck survivor exceeded that of the Columbine tragedy, the
Oklahoma City bombing, and the deaths of John F. Kennedy Jr. and
Princess Diana combined, the group said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Elian's story has been especially alluring, combining a
photogenic boy, family ties and serious international political
issues,'' CMPA President Dr. Robert Lichter. ''The story was a
current events cocktail, with equal parts People magazine and Wall
Street Journal-type story lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the ''big three'' networks, ABC was responsible for more
than 38 percent of the boy's coverage, CBS more than 34 percent and
NBC with more than 26 percent of the total stories, the study
found.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Election 2000, the study found that the Gonzalez case
has dominated the network newscasts this year, surpassing the next
six stories combined: rising gas prices, the New York Senate race,
the war in Chechnya, the crash of Alaska Airlines Flight 261, Pope
John Paul II's trip to the Middle East and the Justice Department's
continued battle with Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the networks aired 431 stories on Simpson, who was
acquitted of the murder of his ex-wife and a friend, while so far
this year, the networks have aired 363 stories about Gonzalez's
plight, the research found.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, there were 336 stories on the Oklahoma City
bombing in 1995, 319 on the Columbine shooting last year, 211 on
the World Trade Center bombing in 1993, 200 on the death of
Princess Diana in 1997 and 161 on the death of Kennedy last year,
the study showed.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Center for Media and Public Affairs
http://www.cmpa.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
