<HEADLINE> After years of trying, city on verge of getting public toilets  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - After years of debate about whether providing
public toilets would be more harmful than helpful, the city is
finally prepared to take the plunge by spending $5 million to
install at least 50 privies around town.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the budget deal worked out this week between the City
Council and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, the city will spend $1 million
the fiscal year beginning July 1 and $4 million the next year to
build the commodes. The first toilets could be operational within
18 months.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the City Council passed the budget 48-0, including
funding for the commodes.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear yet how much the toilets will cost to use or to
maintain or where they will be placed. Some of the city's cost will
likely be offset by advertisements placed on the structures housing
the commodes.
</P>
<P>
   For years, city officials have debated whether to install public
toilets. After concerns were raised about the cost of such an
effort and the safety of those using the facilities, the issue went
nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   But recently, City Council Speaker Peter Vallone - who was
impressed by public toilets he saw during a European vacation -
pushed hard for the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ''The issue of public toilets has been sitting dormant for
years, the victim of bureaucracy, politics and inefficacy,'' said
Vallone. ''Finally, I said enough is enough. ... New York is a
world class city and our citizens and visitors deserve this very
basic service.''
</P>
</TEXT>
