<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Justices Back Rule of Law Elsewhere  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE ASSEO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- One-third of the Supreme Court appeared before
an international audience Tuesday to promote the rule of law in
other nations. One justice's suggestion: put court decisions on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would like to see written opinions of high courts around the
globe, written, interpreted in several languages and put on Web
sites so that the world can see what you're doing,'' Justice Sandra
Day O'Connor said at a World Bank-sponsored conference on legal and
judicial development.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy said it is important for judges on
the new European Court of Human Rights to ''begin writing decisions
which have the capacity and the power to inspire and to persuade.''
</P>
<P>
   Nations' economies depend on having a fair and effective legal
system, because without it people will not invest there, added
Justice Stephen G. Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy told the audience that while the U.S. legal system took
hundreds of years to develop, other nations that lacked independent
judicial systems until now must act quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are entitled to democracy, they are entitled to
legitimacy, they are entitled to a recognition of their humanity,
and they are entitled to it now,'' Kennedy said. ''We have to teach
that law is a liberating force and it's not an oppressive force.''
</P>
<P>
   Breyer said the idea is not to impose one country's legal system
on another country, and his colleagues acknowledged that the U.S.
system has its flaws. Asked whether local judges who are elected --
rather than appointed -- are vulnerable to political power and less
independent, O'Connor answered with a simple ''yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy added, ''It will never change, and what you must do in
the United States is to teach the public ... the necessity of
strong, courageous, principled judges who are entitled to be
re-elected despite unpopular decisions, and if the American public
doesn't understand that, it's in big trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how courts can be made more accessible to the poor,
Kennedy said legal aid programs provided a ''necessary safety valve
for the stability of government'' by allowing the voice of the poor
to be heard.
</P>
<P>
   A free press also is necessary, Breyer said. U.S. federal judges
are required to file financial disclosure forms every year, an
exercise he called annoying but necessary to convince the public
''that everything is above board.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Supreme Court site: http://www.supremecourtus.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-06-00 1725 </TRAILER>
