<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mideast Peace Talks To Head to D.C.  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel and the Palestinians agreed Tuesday to
resume negotiations after a two-week lapse, but despite prodding by
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright they remained far apart on
terms of a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The future of Jerusalem, one of the main issues, has not been
formally discussed, a senior U.S. official said. Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak wants it to be taken up later, said the
official, who briefed reporters on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not close to an agreement,'' Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy said. He said it was not clear that the Palestinians
wanted to move toward the agreement the two sides promised by
mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   On the Palestinian side, Yasser Arafat demanded Israel make good
on a promised third pullback on the West Bank and said Israel
should quit the West Bank under 1967 and 1973 U.N. Security Council
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   Against that backdrop, Israeli and Palestinian negotiators will
reopen their talks in the Washington area early next week, and
Arafat will call on President Clinton at the White House June 14.
</P>
<P>
   There is a slight chance Barak might join them for a three-way
summit, but ''there is too much to do, and we are not there yet,''
the U.S. official said.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, with King Abdullah II of Jordan at his side,
Clinton said, ''We're working at it, and I'm encouraged.'' But he
added: ''You know, it's not going to be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   The president pledged to do whatever he can to further peace.
''We're down to the difficult issues and difficult decisions,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   After talks with Clinton, Abdullah met with members of Congress.
The king told reporters he thought peacemaking between Israel and
the Palestinians generally is moving the right direction. ''I think
that people keep looking at the pessimistic side of things,'' he
said. ''You're going to have obstacles in the road.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli-Palestinian talks would last about a week. The
Washington-area location was not disclosed and may be kept secret
even after senior Israeli and Palestinian negotiators begin their
discussions, the official who briefed reporters said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright underscored the negotiations' precarious stage. ''We
are at a moment of truth when it is necessary for us all to roll up
our sleeves and work,'' she said. ''The United States is prepared
to help, but ultimately, the hard decisions have to be made by the
parties themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   These include how much territory the Palestinians are to get
from Israel for a state and whether its capital will be in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, after calling on Arafat at his office in the West Bank
town of Ramallah, said he pledged ''to do his part'' to conclude an
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know there are those who say that the negotiations cannot
succeed in fulfilling Palestinian aspirations,'' Albright said.
''Those voices belong to the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak has accused Arafat of foot-dragging, an accusation
Palestinian negotiators have hurled at Israelis in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat dismissed the complaint. ''We have demonstrated over and
over our many flexibilities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat declined to say, however, whether the talks had reached a
point where a three-way summit hosted by Clinton would be useful.
And while he spoke in praise of the late Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin as a partner in a joint quest for peace, Arafat would not say
whether he has changed his mind about Barak, whom he had praised
similarly in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am not prepared to answer this question,'' the Palestinian
leader said, ''because I believe this question tends to destroy the
Palestinian-Israeli relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright concluded her talks in Jerusalem with a second meeting
with Barak. On Wednesday, she flies to Cairo to meet with Syrian
Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa and Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak among other Arab leaders at a conference there.
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.S. official said at the start of Albright's three-day
trip to the region that it would require at least one more visit to
arrange a three-way summit in the United States, and even then
there are bound to be differences remaining between the two sides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
