<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Meets With Jordan King  </HEADLINE>
By WALTER R. MEARS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- After telling eastern Europeans that the
struggles of building open economies on the ruins of communism will
pay dividends in future prosperity, President Clinton was back at
the White House today, conferring with a leader from the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, with King Abdullah II of Jordan at his side, said he is
encouraged by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's announcement
today that Israeli and Palestinian negotiators will return to the
Washington area early next week.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're working at it and I'm encouraged,'' Clinton said before
an Oval Office meeting with Abdullah. ''You know, it's not going to
be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright announced the shift after meeting in Ramallah, on the
West Bank, with Yasser Arafat. She also said the Palestinian leader
would call on Clinton at the White House June 14.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton left open the possibility of a Camp David-style summit
together with Israeli and Palestinian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're down to the difficult issues and difficult decisions,''
Clinton said as he pledged to do whatever he can to further peace.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton returned to Washington from Kiev, Ukraine, Monday night,
ending a journey in which he repeatedly urged openings to the West
for and by Russia and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   That was his 48th foreign journey as president; his 49th is
later this week, to Tokyo, for the funeral of a Japanese prime
minister and to meet with his successor.
</P>
<P>
   At weekend summit meetings with Russian President Vladimir Putin
and in a speech to the Russian parliament on Monday, Clinton said
European unity and institutions should not end at the borders of
the old Soviet Union, but should reach to Moscow and Kiev.
</P>
<P>
   He had sounded the same message to western Europe, in meetings
and speeches in Lisbon, Berlin and Aachen, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The finale was in Kiev, to tens of thousands of Ukranians in the
broad plaza and mall of St. Michael's Square.
</P>
<P>
   ''From Lithuania to Poland to the Czech Republic, those who
chose open societies and open markets like you started out with
sacrifice but they ended up with success,'' Clinton said. ''I
believe Ukraine has the best opportunity in a thousand years to
achieve freedom and prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a presidential performance with a holiday air. Ukranian
rock stars played to the crowd standing in the hot sun, in a
sweeping mall between golden domed cathedrals. A giant American
flag hung over them, hundreds of yards down the mall from the
yellow and blue draped platform where Clinton spoke. The Odessa
Symphony Orchestra was on the plaza at the other side of the
platform. Clinton smiled, kept time and waved at the side of the
conductor when they played ''Take Me Out To The Ball Game.''
</P>
<P>
   He spoke through an interpreter, urging Ukranians to rally in
support of democracy and a reformed, market economy. ''Communism
has lost in Ukraine but a full commitment to free-market democracy
has not yet won,'' he said. ''Do not give up. Keep on fighting.
Boritesya poboroete.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he went to the crowd, shaking hands campaign style along
the barrier in front of the platform. As he finished and headed
home, the bells of blue and white St. Michael's Cathedral, just
rebuilt, rang out over the square.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, with Clinton beside him at the presidential palace,
President Leonid Kuchma announced that the last part of the
Chernobyl nuclear power plant will be closed on Dec. 15, more than
14 years after the worst atomic power accident in history.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced $78 million in U.S. aid for the shutdown, and
said he will seek additional international help for Ukraine. He
promised an additional $2 million in American aid for safety
measures at other Ukranian nuclear plants.
</P>
<P>
   Then the presidents and their official parties toasted the
moment in champagne.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was to make a rapid round trip to Tokyo to attend the
funeral on Thursday of Keizo Obuchi, who died of a stroke on May
14. The Kyodo News Agency said Clinton would hold talks with the
new prime minister, Yoshiro Mori, while he is in Toky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
