<HEADLINE> Clinton Presses Congress on Funds  </HEADLINE>
By DEB RIECHMANN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton chided Congress for failing
to approve emergency money for ''pressing national needs,''
including relief for victims of Hurricane Floyd, help for Colombia
to battle drug traffickers and support for U.S. troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has asked Congress for $5.5 billion for these and other
items that he says cannot wait for next year's budget. The House
approved $13 billion in March, but the Senate chose to break up the
request and attach pieces to next year's spending bills, which
already were being written.
</P>
<P>
   The president's request includes money to do safety maintenance
on the air traffic control system, provide housing help for Floyd's
victims in North Carolina and battle forest fires, especially in
the West. It also includes emergency assistance for families who
struggled through the winter with high heating oil costs and now
face expenses for fans and air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   ''The national interest in Colombia -- and in the other things
that I itemized -- just cries out for action,'' Clinton said. ''This
is funding for pressing national needs, where delay means putting
American families in hardship and our national interests at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Clinton's complaint, Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., said he favors approving anti-drug money for
Colombia but opposes handling the emergency requests in a single
piece of legislation. He said he fears it would attract spending on
lawmakers' pet projects and push the bill's price tag far above the
total of the president's emergency request.
</P>
<P>
   Lott promised to try to find a faster way to approve the money
for Colombia, which he acknowledged was bogged down in a
slow-moving foreign aid bill. ''We'll look for another vehicle to
which that can be attached,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Lott isn't convinced it will pass. ''I don't know where
the votes are,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Ted Stevens, R-Alaska,
blamed Clinton for the budget problems. He said that the president,
without authorization from Congress, has tapped defense accounts
for action in places like Kosovo, forcing lawmakers to find ways to
replenish accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ''He can go blow his wind out all he wants as far as I'm
concerned,'' Stevens said. ''He has not been a fair president in
dealing with the financing of this government. He has caused us
increased costs by the way he's handled this money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
