<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Non-Combat Zone Medals Rethought  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon said Tuesday it is reconsidering
the recent practice of awarding Bronze Star medals -- one of the
highest military honors -- to service members not involved in action
within a combat zone.
</P>
<P>
   The question arose after the military newspaper Stars and
Stripes reported last weekend that its review of Bronze Star
citations for the U.S. air campaign against Yugoslavia last year
showed that a majority went to servicemen far from the combat zone.
</P>
<P>
   At least five Bronze Stars, for example, went to Air Force
officers at Whiteman Air Force Base, Mo., home of the B-2 bombers
which flew roundtrip missions to the Balkans. None were pilots,
since the Defense Department criteria for awarding Bronze Stars
specifically says they are not for ''participation in aerial
flight.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars and Stripes also said Bronze Stars were awarded to three
colonels in Germany who worked on overflight clearances and basing
rights in Europe for U.S. aircraft supporting the air campaign in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Army, which had the most people situated in the combat zone
-- but no one engaged in actual combat -- awarded no Bronze Stars,
the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon regulation on awarding Bronze Stars says they can
be given to a military member who ''distinguishes himself or
herself by heroic or meritorious achievement or service'' under any
of three circumstances:
</P>
<P>
   --''While engaged in an action against an enemy of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   --''While engaged in military operations involving conflict with
an opposing foreign force.''
</P>
<P>
   --While serving with friendly foreign forces in which the United
States is not a belligerent party.
</P>
<P>
   It does not say the military member must be present in the
combat zone, and Pentagon spokesman Rear Adm. Craig Quigley said it
is up to the Air Force and other services to decide how to
interpret the criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Air Force and Navy defended their Bronze Star awards as
appropriate under existing criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Quigley was asked whether the Pentagon is reviewing the
criteria.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll take a look at them,'' he replied. ''I don't have any
sense at this point that the services have somehow inappropriately
applied the criteria, but we'll take a look.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, spokeswoman Lt. Col. Catherine Abbott said the Pentagon
was reconsidering whether the Bronze Star should, as a matter of
policy, be awarded to service members who are not engaged in action
in a combat zone. She said it was not yet clear whether the Bronze
Stars awarded for the Kosovo campaign might be rescinded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-06-00 1750 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000606.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
