<HEADLINE> US Probes Mexico Activist Threat  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration said Tuesday it is
looking into reports that a Mexican activist has offered $10,000 to
anyone who kills a U.S. Border Patrol agent.
</P>
<P>
   ''We take such threats extremely seriously,'' said State
Department spokesman Philip Reeker.
</P>
<P>
   The bounty was offered by Carlos Ibarra Perez, president of the
Citizens Defense Committee, which contends that undocumented
Mexican aliens are being mistreated in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The offer was made after a Border Patrol agent killed an
undocumented immigrant two weeks ago in Brownsville, Texas, and
reports surfaced of threats by vigilantes against immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Ibarra Perez expressed anger at the treatment of illegal
immigrants near Douglas, Ariz., where armed ranchers have patrolled
the border, guarding against trespassing and vandalism by
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Reeker said the United States is ''very much committed to
working with the Mexican authorities to promote border safety.''
</P>
<P>
   At a high-level Washington meeting last month, the United States
and Mexico agreed to intensify efforts to curb the smuggling of
Mexicans into Arizona and their illegal detention by vigilante
groups once they cross the border.
</P>
</TEXT>
