<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Down 80; Nasdaq Drops 65  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks closed mostly lower Tuesday as investors
collected profits after a three-day winning streak. Financial and
retail issues fell as investors worried that an economic slowdown
would hurt those business sectors.
</P>
<P>
   Many stocks drifted between gains and losses as investors waited
for a new catalyst for the market.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know that you can make a whole lot out of the market's
activity until the next time we have some concrete news to trade
off of,'' said Charles White, president and portfolio manager at
Avatar Associates in New York. ''There's nothing definitive or
compelling right now that's going to give the market direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 79.73 to close at
10,735.57.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also lower, having given up early
gains. The Nasdaq composite index fell 65.39 to 3,756.37 and the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 9.79 to 1,457.84.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks had risen in the past three sessions on investors' hopes
that the economy has slowed enough to persuade the Federal Reserve
to stop raising interest rates. But Tuesday, investors changed
strategy, selling stocks that are seen as vulnerable to economic
slowdowns.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan fell $3.75 to $133.375 contributed most to the Dow's
decline. Merrill Lynch analyst Judah Kraushaar told clients periods
of rising interest rates have typically been bad for investment
banking revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of many prominent retailers also fell as investors
reasoned that signs of a slowdown in consumer spending could mean
retailers will see revenue and profits slide. Circuit City plunged
$12.625 to $39.50 after saying sales were flat in May.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Circuit City's warning convinced investors that
other retailers will also struggle in the coming months. Wal-Mart
fell $1.188 to $58.125.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, analysts said investors appeared to be
regrouping after sharp gains last week. The Nasdaq, which had been
battered in March and April, soared a record-breaking 19 percent
last week as investors flocked back to the technology stock that
dominate its ranks. The Dow, which hadn't suffered as badly, rose
4.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''The market's doing extremely well after last week's screamer,
which set us up for a little profit-taking,'' said Ralph Bloch,
chief market analyst at Raymond James &AMP; Associates in St.
Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while some investors were indeed cashing in stocks to
capture gains, more stocks rose than fell in the overall market for
much of the session.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's some good underlying strength,'' Bloch said. ''That's
the sign of a market engaging in a healthy pause.''
</P>
<P>
   Stocks that fell prey to profit-takers included Sun
Microsystems, which lost $4.313 to $83.875.
</P>
<P>
   But a broad range of technology stocks advanced. Microsoft rose
$2.75 to $69.625 and Healtheon/Web MD rose $1.313 to $20.063.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the Nasdaq, Starbucks rose $1.875 to $37.50. The coffee
company will be added to the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 on Wednesday,
prompting many index fund managers to buy the stock so that their
portfolios will continue to mirror the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   Trading volume remained fairly low as investors opted to wait
for more information on the strength of the U.S. economy before
taking significant new positions. The next potentially
market-moving report will reach traders Friday, when the Labor
Department releases the Producer Price Index.
</P>
<P>
   A benign report could propel the market higher, White said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a boatload of cash on the sidelines,'' he said. ''More
evidence of a slowdown could be material for a very strong summer
rally.''
</P>
<P>
   Composite volume totaled 1.13 billion shares on the New York
Stock Exchange, compared with 1.02 billion in the previous session.
Advancing issues on the exchange outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9
margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 1.65 to close
at 511.65.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.2 percent.
Germany's Xetra DAX index fell 0.7 percent, France's CAC-40 lost
1.0 percent, and Britain's FT-SE 100 index closed fractionally
higher.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
