<HEADLINE> Insurgent legislator angry at Silver  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A state assemblyman, angry at Speaker
Sheldon Silver for allowing debate on controversial legislation at
the same time as Italian-American lawmakers were to meet for an
annual dinner, said Tuesday it wouldn't have happened if he were
black, Hispanic, Irish or Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Seminerio, a Queens Democrat, said that ''in his little
mind, he thought he was getting even with me'' for supporting
former Majority Leader Michael Bragman's recent unsuccessful
attempt to oust fellow Democrat Silver from the Assembly's top job.
</P>
<P>
   Seminerio was among the organizers of the annual dinner for the
Italian-American state legislators. More than 400 people had
tickets to Monday night's event at an Italian-American community
center in nearby Troy, Seminerio said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It never happens with the Black and Puerto Rican caucus or
with Irish affairs,'' Seminerio said. ''And if is a Jewish holiday,
he (Silver) is out of here by 1 o'clock in the afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver, an Orthodox Jew, carefully observes the Jewish sabbath
and other holy days.
</P>
<P>
   At about the time people were to gather for the Italian-American
dinner at 6 p.m. Monday, the state Assembly was asked to begin
debate on a series of bills designed to reduce the number of
incidents where police shoot or beat innocent citizens.
</P>
<P>
   As the debate dragged on, Seminerio incurred the wrath of the
Assembly's black and Hispanic members - who were speaking
passionately in favor of the bills - by asking for a motion to
adjourn the Assembly so members and their families could go to the
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Seminerio then asked for a slow roll call of members to show his
frustration as Monday night's session continued. The chamber did
not complete its work until after 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   By the time most Assembly members got to the event, ''all the
people were gone, all the ceremonies were over,'' Seminerio said.
</P>
<P>
   Silver dismissed Monday night's brouhaha.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't explain Tony Seminerio,'' the speaker told WROW-AM in
Albany Tuesday. ''I think he's been around here a long time and
feels he can do what's good for Tony Seminerio.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver spokeswoman Patricia Lynch later said the work of the
Assembly was delayed into the early evening Monday because sponsors
of the legislation had arranged to have the families of several
well-publicized cases of police shootings in New York City come to
Albany to promote the measures. The family members were late, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was no ulterior motive,'' Lynch said. ''That was a very
important package of bills, bills that matter a great deal to a
number of our members.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Seminerio's charge that Silver is inconsiderate of
Italian-Americans but not of Jews, Irish or minority legislators,
Lynch said she had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   The outspoken, conservative Seminerio has frequently run afoul
of Silver and other Democrats. He has often endorsed Republicans
rather than Democrats and has said of this year's highest-profile
Democratic candidate: ''If Satan ran against Hillary (Clinton), I'd
vote for Satan.''
</P>
<P>
   Seminerio was one of 19 Democrats who voted May 22 in favor of a
motion that could have led to balloting for a news speaker. Most
Democrats stuck with Silver and he retained his post.
</P>
<P>
   Seminerio said the Italian-American legislators' association is
active in Albany, meeting once or twice a month while the
Legislature is in session. The association has around 60 members,
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
