<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Senate passes pesticide notification bill  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Legislation that would give counties and New
York City the option of adopting laws governing how neighbors are
to be notified when pesticides are in use won passage Tuesday in
the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, local governments that opt to adopt laws would
require homeowners and businesses to give two days advance
notification to neighbors when spraying pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   The distance of advance notification would vary according to the
height of shrubbery being sprayed. Notice would be required to
property owners within 150 feet where vegetation being sprayed is 5
feet tall or greater. For spraying vegetation less than 5 feet
tall, property owners within 15 feet would have to be made aware.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would also require retailers to post informational
signs if they are selling general-use pesticides for residential or
commercial application. In addition, the bill would establish
penalties for violation of the local laws.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Carl Marcellino, a Nassau County Republican and the
bill's sponsor, predicted that ''most counties'' would eventually
opt into the program.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe they have a right as a local municipality to
determine their own fate,'' Marcellino said. ''I believe they'll do
the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which passed 56-2, generated some debate on the Senate
floor because it did not require all counties to adopt the rules.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Richard Dollinger, who voted against the measure,
said that the bill would allow municipalities to add on to existing
rules, resulting in non-uniform laws governing different parts of
the state. The Rochester Democrat said he favored the Assembly
version of a notification bill - passed in January - which made it
mandatory for all municipalities to adopt the laws.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think this (the Senate's) bill goes quite far
enough,'' Dollinger said.
</P>
<P>
   Marcellino said Dollinger's assumption is ''wrong'' because the
issue is one ''strictly to be done by the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Assembly bill, the Senate version also doesn't
include schools or daycare centers and doesn't require homeowners
to give advance notice when granular pesticides are used.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Eric Schneiderman, D-Manhattan, introduced an
amendment that would have made the Senate bill more similar to the
Assembly bill, but the amendment was defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Marcellino said schools would be notified in advance if spraying
is done around their property line and that other decisions
regarding pesticide use should be up to local school boards.
</P>
<P>
   He added that advance notice is not necessary when homeowners
apply granular pesticides because there is no risk until after the
pesticide is used. When that happens, homeowners would have already
put up warning signs required by law.
</P>
<P>
   Marcellino said he hopes the Assembly and Senate will iron out
differences and reach a compromise before the legislative session
ends later this month.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly sponsor of the bill, Democrat Thomas DiNapoli of
Nassau County, agreed and added, ''We remain optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   If enacted, the bill would go into effect March 1, 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-06-00 1810 </TRAILER>
