<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Accused of Kosovo War Crime  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Amnesty International accused NATO forces
Tuesday of unlawfully killing civilians in Kosovo and branded one
attack that killed 16 as a war crime.
</P>
<P>
   NATO said the allegations were ''baseless and ill-founded'' but
acknowledged it made some mistakes that led to civilian deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ''NATO forces violated the laws of war leading to cases of
unlawful killing of civilians,'' the U.S. chapter of the human
rights group said in releasing a 60-page report.
</P>
<P>
   ''NATO did not always meet its legal obligations in selecting
targets and in choosing means and methods of attack.''
</P>
<P>
   The report came just days after the chief U.N. war crimes
prosecutor, Carla del Ponte, said there was no basis for a U.N.
investigation into allegations of NATO war crimes. Del Ponte said
Friday that ''although some mistakes were made by NATO ... there
was no deliberate targeting of civilians or unlawful military
targets.''
</P>
<P>
   The Amnesty International report examined a number of attacks in
the 78-day bombing campaign, including those that struck railroad
bridges, convoys of displaced civilians and the headquarters of
Serbian state television.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bombing of the headquarters of Serbian state radio and
television, which left 16 civilians dead, appears to have been a
deliberate attack on a civilian target and as such constitutes a
war crime,'' said William F. Schulz, executive director of Amnesty
International USA.
</P>
<P>
   ''Civilian deaths could have been significantly reduced if NATO
forces had fully adhered to the laws of war during Operation Allied
Force.''
</P>
<P>
   The group said in some of the other attacks, NATO did not
suspend bombing after it was evident that civilians were struck.
And in two other instances, NATO did not take ''sufficient
precautions'' to minimize civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   NATO said in a statement reacting to the report that it
''scrupulously adhered to international law, including the law of
war, throughout the conflict and made every effort to minimize
civilian casualties.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement repeated, however, acknowledgment that ''among
over 10,000 bombing missions, in a few cases mistakes were made, or
weapons malfunctioned, leading to civilian deaths or injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We deeply regret such incidents,'' NATO said. ''But such
incidents must be weighed against the atrocities that NATO's
actions stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty based its conclusions on ''available evidence, including
NATO's own statements'' from a February meeting with officials of
the alliance and from NATO's operation reports.
</P>
<P>
   The report also drew information from the International
Committee of the Red Cross and the United Nations High Commissioner
for Human Rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-06-00 1811 </TRAILER>
