<DOCNO> APW20000606.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Retirement Plan Questioned  </HEADLINE>
By ALICE ANN LOVE
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An opposition group of private experts said
Tuesday that George W. Bush would need to couple his proposal for
new Social Security investment accounts with benefit cuts or new
spending to plug the retirement program's impending cash shortage.
</P>
<P>
   Bush responded with a pledge to maintain benefits for current
and near retirees.
</P>
<P>
   ''People should not be misled,'' said Robert Ball, one of Social
Security's first administrators, who joined the economists and
academics at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the Republican presidential contender who was campaigning
in Augusta, Ga., promised to keep Social Security the same for
current and near retirees. But he said ''to make sure there is a
Social Security system for the younger generation, we must think
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on Capitol Hill, Republican Sens. Phil Gramm of Texas
and Judd Gregg of New Hampshire rushed to Bush's defense at a news
conference of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whatever we do on investments ... we are much better off by
having that amount of wealth to help us pay for these benefits,''
Gramm said.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg said an alternative proposal by Bush's Democratic
presidential rival, Vice President Al Gore, is ''a shell-game
approach to solving the Social Security problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore favors pumping interest savings from paying down the debt
into Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, appearing Tuesday on ABC's ''Good Morning America,'' said
he opposes private investment of a portion of the taxes used to
fund Social Security because ''it doesn't offset the funding
shortfall. It makes it a lot worse because Social Security writes
checks to those who are retired with money that is contributed each
week and each month by people who are now working.''
</P>
<P>
   The private experts criticizing Bush included Henry Aaron, a
former Carter administration official, now at the Brookings
Institution; Alicia Munnell, a former member of President Clinton's
Council of Economic Advisers, now a Boston College professor, and
Princeton University economics professor Alan Blinder. Munnell and
Blinder have made campaign appearances with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In a report, they said that if nothing is done, a single
average-earning American turning 30 in 2002 can expect retirement
benefits 21 percent lower than what Social Security now promises
because of a cash shortfall that will develop as baby boomers
retire.
</P>
<P>
   If some Social Security payroll taxes are diverted into personal
investment accounts, as Bush has proposed, the shortfall would
increase in the short term. In the long term, the return on young
workers' individual investments would help close the gap.
</P>
<P>
   Most lawmakers and experts agree some shortfall would remain,
however.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, legislation to create personal investment
accounts -- including separate bills sponsored by Gramm and Gregg --
typically includes other changes, such as a higher retirement age
or cash infusions to Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Bush has not said what he would do, and supports
creating a bipartisan congressional commission to help make such
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the opposition report said that, under Bush's
partial plan, the remaining Social Security benefit shortfall for
people now nearing age 30 could be 20 percent -- nearly the same as
if nothing were done. It also said Bush's five-year, $483 billion
tax cut proposal could rule out government surpluses as a future
source of cash to fill that hole.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm argued that high investment returns could greatly improve
Social Security's financial standing.
</P>
<P>
   ''Will investment solve the whole problem? I think it will, but
we won't know until we make the investment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Aaron said there was potential for bad investments to
worsen the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our analysis shows that workers with individual accounts under
this plan would generally not do better than under the current
system, but would be exposed to significant financial risk,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
