<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-CT--Boy Witness, 1st Ld-Writethru,350  </HEADLINE>
Jury rehears testimony in boy witness case
dlfons
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) - The jury in the trial of a man accused
in the murders of an 8-year-old boy and his mother spent Tuesday
rehearing testimony from witnesses and listening to the judge
repeat portions of his instruction on the law.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Peeler is accused of arranging the murders of Leroy
''B.J.'' Brown Jr. and his mother, Karen Clarke.
</P>
<P>
   The boy had been scheduled to testify against Peeler in another
murder case.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say Peeler, 28, asked his younger brother, Adrian,
25, to kill the mother and son to silence the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Peeler will stand trial later. Both brothers face the
possibility of the death penalty if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors began their deliberations at about 2:45 p.m. Monday after
hearing instructions from Superior Court Judge G. Sarsfield Ford.
Less than an hour later, they sent the judge a note asking for the
complete testimony and statements of 14 witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the jury narrowed down their request to portions of
that testimony. Jurors heard a court clerk read back excerpts of
testimony from five witnesses, including Josephine Lee, the state's
star witness.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who lived across the street from B.J. and his mother,
testified that she overheard Russell ask his brother to kill the
pair. Lee also claimed she acted as a lookout and heard the boy cry
out for his mother as Adrian Peeler chased them up the stairs of
their home and shot them to death on Jan. 7, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Peeler's defense lawyers, however, showed the jury letters Lee
wrote in which she denies knowing anything about the murders and
claims she lied about the Peelers' involvement.
</P>
<P>
   At the jury's request, the judge on Tuesday reiterated portions
of his instruction on the four charges against Peeler, including
murder, conspiracy to commit murder and two counts of capital
felony. The jury was also given a written outline of the elements
of the charges.
</P>
<P>
   The jury was expected to rehear additional testimony Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
