<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000606.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Donor's ex-aide admits obstructing campaign finance investigation  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - The former aide to a major political donor
pleaded guilty Tuesday to obstructing a Justice Department
investigation into campaign contributions made by her boss, David
Chang.
</P>
<P>
   The plea by Audrey Yu came on the day she and Chang were to
stand trial. Chang pleaded guilty on Friday to illegally donating
$53,700 to the successful 1996 Senate campaign of then-Rep. Robert
Torricelli.
</P>
<P>
   Like Chang and others from Bergen County who have pleaded
guilty, Yu has agreed to cooperate with the Campaign Financing Task
Force.
</P>
<P>
   Yu, 32, faces six to 12 months in prison but could get probation
for pleading guilty to a single charge of conspiring with Chang to
obstruct justice by backdating a document from Bright &AMP; Bright, a
Chang company.
</P>
<P>
   As part of her plea bargain, Yu acknowledged that she lied to a
federal grand jury last year when she said she did not see shredded
documents at the Englewood Cliffs offices of another Chang company,
Hudson Realty Management Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Chang operates several trading companies, including Bright &AMP;
Bright, Nikko Enterprises Inc., and Panacom in the former
congressional district of Torricelli, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli spokesman Richard McGrath said they had no comment on
Yu because her activities did not involve the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Yu had faced 10 counts, including obstruction and lying to the
grand jury. Unlike those against Chang, none of the charges
involved arranging or coordinating illegal ''conduit'' donations.
</P>
<P>
   Court papers filed with Yu's plea said her admissions do not
include other information she has given to prosecutors. Officials
did not disclose details on that information Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Yu is among 25 people charged by the task force. Six, not
including Yu, have admitted wrongdoing regarding Torricelli
fund-raising efforts. None of the six has implicated the New Jersey
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli is not accused of any wrongdoing. He has maintained
he was unaware of the improper donations. All such money is donated
to charity, he has said.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli raised $9.2 million to defeat Rep. Richard A. Zimmer
in 1996. His fund-raising ability led to his appointment as
chairman of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   At his plea, Chang acknowledged conspiring to break donation
laws with Cha-Kuek ''Charles'' Koo, an executive with a South
Korean conglomerate; Berek Paul Don, a former Bergen County
Republican leader; and Don's former law partner, Carmine Alampi, a
Democratic leader in Bergen County; and unnamed others.
</P>
<P>
   Federal rules bar corporate contributions. Individuals can
contribute up to $2,000 to a candidate during an election cycle -
primary and general election. Reimbursements are not permitted.
</P>
<P>
   Chang and Koo admitted evading restrictions by secretly repaying
''straw donors'' - those who supposedly made the contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Don and Alampi pleaded guilty last year to charges related to
soliciting $11,000 worth of donations to the Torricelli campaign,
which Chang admitted he reimbursed.
</P>
<P>
   Chang, 57, of Cresskill, also admitted he collected $21,000 for
the Torricelli campaign in December 1996, improperly reimbursing
donors with Bright &AMP; Bright money.
</P>
<P>
   Koo pleaded guilty on Thursday to recruiting eight ''straw''
donors at Chang's behest, and Chang on Friday admitted that he gave
Koo $20,000 in cash to reimburse those donors.
</P>
<P>
   Koo, 54, of Alpine, a South Korean citizen, is president of LG
Group's executive office for the Americas in Englewood Cliffs. The
LG Group is one of South Korea's largest conglomerates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-06-00 1832 </TRAILER>
