<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latest bid by NU, ConEd for merger fails to gain state support  </HEADLINE>
By NATASHA GURAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - In its effort to gain the state's
approval of their planned merger, Northeast Utilities and
Consolidated Edison Inc. of New York made a new proposal Tuesday to
Connecticut regulators that promises a extended rate freeze, and
new jobs in the state.
</P>
<P>
   But Attorney General Richard Blumenthal called the plan
inadequate, and said it does not guarantee rate cuts for
Connecticut consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission a week ago approved the
merger, but negotiations toward state support of the deal stalled
in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The $7.5 billion deal would create the country's largest
electric and gas distribution company, with more than 6.4 million
customers in New York and New England.
</P>
<P>
   The latest proposal before the state Department of Public
Utility Control, promises a rate freeze until 2006, a reduction of
regulatory assets by $50 million upon closing of the merger, the
creation up to 600 new jobs in Connecticut, and improved customer
service and reliability.
</P>
<P>
   The companies also agreed to submit to an independent study of
the unregulated electricity market for two years following approval
of the merger. And they promised to work with the state Department
of Environmental Protection to preserve as open space, land that
might be sold off after the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ''The latest proposal seems to be an effort to meet my concerns
about the merger's effects on consumers, our economy, and our
environment,'' said Attorney General Richard Blumenthal. ''It
contains some positive concessions, but clearly it does not go far
enough to provide the benefits and safeguards that I believe are
necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said he will continue to push the DPUC to reject the
merger unless the utilities come up with a more detailed plan that
includes a firm commitment to rate reductions.
</P>
<P>
   The latest offer does not make any commitments regarding
environmental protection and no specific commitment to open space
preservation, Blumenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal also wants the companies to promise not to make
customers pay for executive severance packages, which he claims
could cost up to $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   The federal panel approved the proposed merger without comment
after the utilities allayed concerns about the effect it would have
on competition.
</P>
<P>
   The companies said they have already spun off most of their
power-generation assets in order to comply with electric
deregulation laws. NU sold its fossil fuel plants in Connecticut
and Massachusetts well above book value and has put its Millstone
nuclear power plants up for auction.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders from both companies have already approved the
merger.
</P>
<P>
   The merger still needs approval from regulators in Connecticut,
New York and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   For the past month the DPUC has been negotiating with the
utilities over rate cuts, job protections, corporate donations,
land preservation and other benefits for customers and the state.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission and the U.S. Nuclear
Regulatory Commission must also approve the deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
