<HEADLINE> New York travel writer missing in Jamaica  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEGRIL, Jamaica (AP) - A New York-based travel writer has gone
missing from Jamaica's Negril resort, police said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Claudia Kirschhoch, 29, was last seen singing and dancing around
11 a.m. on May 30 in the lobby of the Sandals Beaches Negril hotel,
a police statement said.
</P>
<P>
   A woman resembling Kirschhoch was reportedly seen later that day
at Alfred's Bar and Restaurant in the resort town, but police said
they were unable to confirm whether that was the missing travel
writer.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Fred Kirschhoch, is offering a reward for
information leading to her whereabouts, the U.S. Embassy said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Kirschhoch, a writer for the U.S. Frommer's Travel Guides,
arrived in Jamaica at Montego Bay on May 24 with three other
reporters en route to visit a Cuban resort of the Jamaican-based
Sandals resort chain, the U.S. Embassy said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   When the Cuban trip was canceled, she and a colleague, Tanya
Grossinger, took up the company's offer to stay at its Negril
hotel, and went there the following day, according to the embassy.
The colleague left May 27 and Kirschhoch was supposed to leave the
Caribbean island June 1, police said.
</P>
<P>
   When she did not return to the hotel to check out, managers
entered her room and, finding her luggage, travel documents and
other personal effects, alerted police.
</P>
</TEXT>
