<HEADLINE> Clinton Heading to Japan  </HEADLINE>
By SONYA ROSS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Undeterred by the prospect of two long flights
on top of fresh jet lag, President Clinton is heading abroad again
to pay his personal respects to Japan's late prime minister, Keizo
Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to leave Wednesday morning for Tokyo to
join other world leaders at a memorial service for Obuchi, who
suffered a stroke in April and died May 14. This foreign journey --
Clinton's 49th as president -- comes just a day after Clinton
returned from a six-day trip to Europe and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   It also was sandwiched between Tuesday's White House meeting
with King Abdullah of Jordan and Friday's visit by Mexican
President Ernesto Zedillo. While in Tokyo, Clinton will meet with
Obuchi's successor, Yoshiro Mori, and South Korean President Kim
Dae-jung.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will be gone for about 36 hours, with all but 10 spent
flying to and from Tokyo, White House aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Clinton and Kim, other heads of state and governments
attending the service include the presidents of the Philippines,
Indonesia, Palau and Micronesia and the prime ministers of
Malaysia, Australia, Thailand and Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will meet with Mori as soon as he arrives, the
administration official said. After the memorial service, Clinton
will speak at the home of Ambassador Thomas Foley.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ''will not have significant things to say'' in his
speech about issues such as trade, the U.S. military presence on
Okinawa or the coming G-8 economic summit, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The American president also will meet with Kim to discuss next
week's summit between Kim and his North Korean counterpart, Kim
Jong Il. Then, Clinton will attend a reception, hosted by Mori, for
visiting world leaders before returning to Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
