<HEADLINE> Queen Meets Holocaust Survivors  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Queen Elizabeth II met Tuesday with survivors of
the Holocaust at the opening of a permanent exhibition documenting
Nazi persecution during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The queen, accompanied by husband Prince Philip, looked somber
as she viewed exhibits at the Imperial War Museum that included a
funeral cart used to collect the dead in the Warsaw ghetto, a rail
car used to transport Jews to concentration camps and filmed
testimony of survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Survivor Esther Brunstein told the queen the exhibition had
transported her ''back to a time when I lived on another planet
when evil reigned supreme.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Just to survive one day in the camp and retain a sense of
humanity was itself an act of resistance,'' Brunstein said. ''Yet
atrocities go on in the world today, and the tragedy is that we
still haven't learned the lesson.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
