<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio questions Clinton's ability to work in Senate chambers  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) - Republican Rick Lazio on Tuesday
questioned whether his campaign rival, Hillary Rodham Clinton,
could work effectively in the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there is a very questionable record when it comes to
working in a bipartisan fashion,'' the little-known Long Island
congressman said following a speech to the New York State
Conference of Mayors and Other Municipal Officials.
</P>
<P>
   ''New Yorkers have every right to ask ... can you demonstrate to
us that you can work in a bipartisan fashion?'' Lazio told a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Questioning the first lady's ability to work effectively in the
Senate echoed a theme Clinton had used against former Republican
Senate candidate, New York City Mayor Rudy Giuliani. The first lady
had repeatedly raised questions about Giuliani's temperament and
ability to work with others. Lazio on Tuesday seemed to be turning
the tables on her.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and the president have had sometimes icy relations with
Republicans in Washington who led the unsuccessful fight to throw
Bill Clinton out of office.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's campaign disputed Lazio's charges.
</P>
<P>
   ''While Rick Lazio followed the party line and cut student
loans, Head Start and Medicare, Hillary Clinton worked in a
bipartisan way to pass laws that provided health care to more than
400,000 New York children and made it easier for New York families
to adopt,'' Clinton spokeswoman Karen Finney said.
</P>
<P>
   In another campaign development, sources within the Lazio
campaign and the Pataki administration said Eileen Long, the chief
of staff to Lt. Gov. Mary Donohue and a daughter of state
Conservative Party Chairman Michael Long, would be taking a leave
of absence from her government post to work in a ''senior
position'' on the Lazio campaign. Ms. Long is extremely close to
Zenia Mucha, Gov. George Pataki's chief political adviser.
</P>
<P>
   After delivering a speech to the mayors about public housing
issues - his most policy wonkish to date - Lazio told reporters he
didn't think much of federal housing policies espoused by the
Clinton administration or federal Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to say anything much disparaging about Andrew
Cuomo, suffice it to say that I think all the leadership in housing
issues has come from the Republican side, particularly in the House
of Representatives,'' Lazio said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the role the federal Department of Housing and Urban
Development had played, Lazio said ''sometimes there was
opposition, sometimes there was disinterest, but we have not had
much in terms of legislative initiatives coming out of the White
House or HUD,'' said Lazio, who chairs the House's Housing
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   David Egner, a spokesman for Cuomo said ''the difference between
the Republicans and Democrats couldn't be more clear.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They (Republicans) wanted to eliminate HUD entirely, stop
housing production, sell the federal housing administration and
kick the poor out of public housing,'' Egner said. ''We (Democrats)
reformed HUD.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech to more than 200 members of the mayors'
conference, Lazio outlined policies for revitalizing downtown areas
and providing affordable housing for New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's something uniquely American about owning your own
place,'' Lazio told the mayors.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that successful public housing requires a mix of
income levels.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't want to concentrate poverty,'' the Republican
congressman said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio also faced questions Tuesday about his owning a vacation
home in an area of Long Island where he is pressing for a
beach-restoration project.
</P>
<P>
   Area real estate agents told the New York Daily News the project
could raise property values for homeowners like Lazio. One critic
of the project questioned the Long Island congressman's championing
of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why is the federal government paying for virtually private
beaches for Rick Lazio and his beach buddies?'' said Jeff Stein of
Taxpayers for Common Sense, a nonpartisan budget watchdog group
opposed to the project.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said the beach house ''has not been a very good
investment'' and that he saw no conflict in pushing the project. He
compared it to fighting for help for local schools in his
congressional district.
</P>
<P>
   ''My record is being an advocate for my community and my
neighborhood,'' Lazio said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan to have the Army Corps of Engineers dredge sand from
the ocean and then pump it onto the beaches of Fire Island just off
the south shore of Long Island is stalled over a funding dispute
between the federal government and New York state and a separate
federal demand for a building moratorium in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the plan say that building up the barrier island
beaches off Long Island's south shore will make the main island
safer from flooding and other possible storm-related damage.
</P>
<P>
   Federal financial disclosure forms filed by Lazio last year
value the vacation home in Fair Harbor on Fire Island at between
$100,000 and $250,000 and say Lazio had rental income from the
property last year of between $5,000 and $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's main home is in Brightwaters, a community on Long Island
not far from Fair Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   -For Lazio campaign: http://www.lazio.com.
</P>
<P>
   -For Clinton campaign: http://www.hillary2000.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
