<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tuesday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Quebec Man Guilty Of First-Degree Murder
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST-JEAN-SUR-RICHELIEU, Quebec (AP) -- A man who admitted to
shooting his wife at a women's shelter was convicted Tuesday of
first-degree murder by a jury.
</P>
<P>
   Marcel Samson, 45, also was convicted of two arson-related
charges for setting their house on fire and pouring gasoline in the
shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Chantale Dufour, 21, was working at the shelter on June 10,
1999, when Samson stormed in and forced her to reveal the
whereabouts of his wife. Dufour cried when the verdict was
announced and hugged supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The defense and Crown didn't dispute that Samson took a shotgun
to the shelter and shot Ginette Roger, 42, six or seven times while
she slept.
</P>
<P>
   The issue for the jury was whether he intended to kill his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Senate Committee: Dying Patients Don't Get Proper Care
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Death in Canada is a disgrace, says a Senate
committee.
</P>
<P>
   No more than 10 percent of incurable patients get good care in
their final days and months, the legal and constitutional affairs
committee says in a report released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Patients are often left to die without adequate pain relief and
without emotional or spiritual comfort, says the report.
</P>
<P>
   Many doctors scrimp on pain medication because they fear
criminal charges if the patient's life is shortened.
</P>
<P>
   Such palliative care programs as do exist tend to focus on
cancer patients. There are fewer services for other diseases like
Alzheimer's, respiratory failure and multiple sclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   Canadians have good reason to be concerned about these issues,
chairwoman Sharon Carstairs said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every single one of us dies. The sad news is that all of you
are going to die and hope you die with quality end-of-life care.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
