<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill To Trim Clinton's Peace Plan  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A House panel approved a spending bill for
next year that would slice President Clinton's plans for U.S.
contributions to United Nations peacekeeping efforts and hinder the
federal lawsuit against the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   By a voice vote Tuesday evening, a subcommittee of the House
Appropriations Committee approved a $34.9 billion measure financing
the departments of State, Commerce and Justice. Overall, it was
$2.7 billion below Clinton's request and $100 million below this
year's level.
</P>
<P>
   Subcommittee Chairman Harold Rogers, R-Ky., called the bill ''a
barebones recommendation'' that will force the administration to
choose priorities. Democrats predicted that money would be added
before the bill is signed into law. The panel's top Democrat, Rep.
Jose Serrano of New York, saying it heeded budget limits set ''when
we could only see a future of deficits.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure's $4.4 billion for the Commerce Department is nearly
$300 million below this year's level. It contains $498 million for
peacekeeping contributions, the same as this year but $241 million
less than Clinton wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers contended the peacekeeping cut was warranted, saying the
United Nations is not equipped to intervene in what he said has
become a full-fledged war in Sierra Leone. But Rep. David Obey,
D-Wis., called the reduction ''a gross dereliction of duty.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure would also forbid the Justice Department from taking
money from other agencies' budgets for the costs of lawsuits unless
they were defending the government.
</P>
<P>
   That, in effect, would make it harder for the department to
pursue its litigation against cigarette companies. The government
is trying to recover billions of dollars it has spent under
Medicare and other programs to treat people with illnesses related
to smoking, and the Justice Department wants other agencies to
share the legal costs.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate version of the same spending bill would also block
the lawsuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-06-00 2048 </TRAILER>
