<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 49ers Waive DE Gabe Wilkins  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) -- Defensive end Gabe Wilkins, who had
just one sack in two seasons after coming to San Francisco as a $20
million free agent, was waived by the 49ers on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The move generated $3.25 million in savings for the salary-cap
strapped 49ers this season but the team will take a $4 million hit
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkins spent his first four years in Green Bay, where he played
opposite Reggie White and established himself as a solid run
defender and pass rusher. Wilkins developed tendinitis in his left
knee during the 1997 season, missed one half of a playoff game and
left the Super Bowl, which the Packers lost to the Denver Broncos,
after one series.
</P>
<P>
   Anxious to bolster their defensive line, the 49ers signed
Wilkins as a free agent but it never panned out. The knee injury
was worse than originally thought and required additional surgery.
</P>
<P>
   He spent half of his first season in San Francisco on the
physically unable to perform list before being activated, appearing
in eight games and starting four.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Wilkins started 15 of 16 games but made little
impact. His only sack in the last two seasons came during a Dec. 18
game against Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   In another move, the 49ers signed linebacker Jason Lamar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-06-00 2110 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000606.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Historic showdown in Democratic primary between big spender, veteran fighter </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Former investment banker Jon Corzine led
former Gov. Jim Florio in very early returns in the Democratic
Senate primary Tuesday after the political newcomer spent a
record-shattering $33 million on his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With 8 percent of precincts reporting, Corzine led with 27,826
votes, or 67 percent. Florio drew 13,760 votes, or 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine has never held elected office but quickly gained
endorsements from key Democratic Party organizations and the key
party leaders, including the man both he and Florio hope to
replace, retiring three-term Democratic Sen. Frank Lautenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Florio is seeking a return to politics after voters dumped him
in 1993 at the end of just one term as governor following his $2.8
billion tax increases.
</P>
<P>
   At Corzine's reception at an East Brunswick hotel, two giant
screens alternated between television news coverage and Corzine's
ubiquitous commercials. About 300 supporters cheered when seeing
early returns with a Corzine lead.
</P>
<P>
   ''I liked his tuition thing and what he did with Social
Security,'' said supporter Frank Lysick, 42, of Linden, who added
he was not disturbed by Corzine's campaign spending.
</P>
<P>
   ''I like it. The guy's rich. I want to be rich someday,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The primary campaign has been decidedly nasty as Florio has
spent most of his time chiding the former chairman of the Goldman
Sachs &AMP; Co. investment firm for a cash takeover of the political
process. Corzine in a $2-million-per-week blitz of TV commercials
has hammered Florio for the tax increases he pushed through as
governor 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Even the chief issue of the campaign, Social Security, has been
discussed with a hard edge.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine has proposed investing a small portion of the Social
Security trust fund into the stock market to build up long-term
security. Florio has denounced it as a reckless risk designed to
benefit Wall Street cronies who would be in line to earn
commissions. Corzine's campaign has denounced Florio as a liar on
the issue because a newspaper tape recording showed he thought it
was a good idea in May 1999 before Corzine entered the race.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine came into the contest Tuesday with substantial
advantages over Florio not only in cash firepower - the former
governor was to have spent only about $2 million - but in
organizational support and high-profile endorsements. A Quinnipiac
College poll released May 25 had placed Corzine 26 points ahead
among likely Democratic primary voters, with a margin of error of
5.1 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine had the official backing of the state Democratic Party
and the Democratic organizations in most of the major counties in
New Jersey covering some two-thirds of the registered Democrats in
the state. Lautenberg had endorsed Corzine and filmed a campaign
commercial with him.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's other U.S. senator, Robert Torricelli, has remained
officially mum on the race but in fact played the major role in
recruiting Corzine. During an embarrassing flap in April when
Corzine apologized for ethnic jokes he reportedly had made about
Italian Americans, Torricelli traveled from Washington to stand by
him at a Newark news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Florio, though a resident of Metuchen, had built his
campaign upon his traditional support in the counties around
Camden, his home turf as congressman for 16 years and his base for
his 1989 victory in the race for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Florio narrowly lost re-election in 1993 to Republican Gov.
Christie Whitman, and Republicans remain in firm control of the
state Senate and Assembly since the fallout over Florio's tax
increases of $2.8 billion caused voters to oust the Democratic
majorities in both houses. The tax increase was a decision Florio
in this campaign still defended assiduously.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-06-00 2112 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000606.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Colo Gov. Named LA Schools Chief  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN SANTOS
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Former Colorado Gov. Roy Romer on Tuesday was
named superintendent of the Los Angeles school system, which has
been struggling with low test scores, fractious leadership and the
threat of state oversight.
</P>
<P>
   Romer, former chairman of the Democratic National Committee,
will take over the nation's second-largest school district, with
711,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   ''The new face of America is going to be developed, in my
judgment, in the L.A. community. You have the potential of being
the premier metropolitan area of the United States,'' Romer said at
a news conference. ''Now, there's one flaw to that. If you do not
make this school system work, you're never going to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Romer, 71, succeeds Ramon Cortines, who was brought in as
interim superintendent in January to begin reforms after the ouster
of Ruben Zacarias.
</P>
<P>
   Zacarias was accused of mismanagement, and he especially came
under fire when it was learned that the nation's most expensive
high school, the Belmont Learning Complex, was being built on a
site suffused with toxic gases left over from its days as an oil
field. After $170 million in construction costs, the project was
scrapped.
</P>
<P>
   Romer beat out two experienced school administrators: former
Chicago Board of Education President George Munoz and an official
of another school district who asked the Los Angeles board to keep
her name private.
</P>
<P>
   Other potential candidates said they withdrew their applications
for superintendent out of fears that the district will be taken
over by the state because of all its problems.
</P>
<P>
   Romer also inherits a district that is being reorganized into 11
semiautonomous mini-districts, each with its own superintendent.
And the contract with teachers expires June 30; they want a 21
percent pay increase, limits on class size and a grievance process
if textbooks are lacking or classrooms aren't clean.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is one of the most exciting jobs in America and it's also
one of the toughest jobs,'' Romer said.
</P>
<P>
   Day Higuchi, president of United Teachers Los Angeles, which
represents 43,000 district teachers, reacted favorably to Romer's
appointment.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was right on today, he made a lot of common sense,''
Higuchi said.
</P>
<P>
   Board of Education President Genethia Hayes announced the
appointment at a hastily called news conference. The board then
returned to closed session and did not immediately comment on its
choice of Romer.
</P>
<P>
   Romer spent nearly 40 years in Colorado government, beginning in
1958, when he was elected to the state House. He served 12 years as
governor, from 1987 to 1999, and was barred by law from seeking a
fourth term.
</P>
<P>
   Romer was appointed general chairman of the Democratic National
Committee in 1997 and left that post last year to become head of
the committee organizing the party's convention in Los Angeles in
August. He will resign that post to take the school position.
</P>
<P>
   His appointment comes three weeks after the nation's largest
school district, the one in New York City, picked a new
superintendent without education experience -- former banking
executive Harold Levy.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado Attorney General Ken Salazar, a former Romer aide, said
Romer ''prioritized education as one of his top issues'' and pushed
for the creation of statewide tests that measure students'
performance and progress.
</P>
<P>
   Salazar also said Romer broke an impasse between Denver teachers
and the school board in the early 1990s by ordering the teachers
not to strike and helping to put together a contract both sides
agreed on.
</P>
<P>
   And the Republican who succeeded Romer, Gov. Bill Owens, said
Romer ''has a long record of commitment to public education which
will serve the district well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-06-00 2115 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000606.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corzine Lead Grows in N.J.  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Former investment banker Jon Corzine held a
wide lead over former Gov. Jim Florio in New Jersey's Democratic
Senate primary Tuesday, after the political newcomer spent a
record-shattering $33 million on his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With 10 percent of precincts reporting, Corzine led with 29,157
votes, or 66 percent. Florio drew 14,908 votes, or 34 percent. Much
of the early vote came from the Democratic stronghold in the Newark
area where Corzine organized well. Florio was doing well in a
smattering of returns from the Camden area, considered to be his
base.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine has never held elected office but quickly gained
endorsements from top state political leaders, including the man
both he and Florio hope to replace, retiring three-term Democratic
Sen. Frank Lautenberg. The race was the highlight of primary voting
in six states Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Florio, seeking a return to politics after voters dumped him in
1993 at the end of just one term because he raised taxes by $2.8
billion, accused Corzine of trying to buy the seat.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's primary spending -- which could work out to as much as
$100 per vote -- shattered the previous U.S. record for an entire
Senate race -- $30 million spent by Republican Michael Huffington in
his losing 1994 bid for office in California.
</P>
<P>
   The former Goldman Sachs chairman unleashed a
$2-million-per-week blitz of TV commercials and poured hundreds of
thousands of dollars into state and county Democratic
organizations. Florio denounced the tactic as a ''hostile corporate
takeover'' of the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Some voters shrugged off the criticism of Corzine's spending.
Norm Reiff, 69, of Northfield, said he picked Corzine, ''in spite
of all the money he put into it.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got a new face,'' Reiff said. ''Let's give him a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Rain throughout the day threatened to keep turnout low.
</P>
<P>
   The attention paid to Corzine's spending and his campaign
platforms, such as federal funding of college for students with B
averages or better and investing Social Security funds in the stock
market, dwarfed interest in the GOP primary for Lautenberg's seat.
</P>
<P>
   After GOP Gov. Christie Whitman said she would not run, four
lesser-known candidates stepped in.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. William Gormley led in early returns with 53 percent
of the total in a four-way race with Rep. Bob Franks, Essex County
Executive Jim Treffinger and Ramapo College professor Murray
Sabrin. The GOP has not won a Senate seat in New Jersey since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday also marked the end of the presidential primary season,
with contests in five of the six states, though they held little
import since George W. Bush and Al Gore locked up their nominations
back in March. The sixth state, Iowa, held its caucuses in January.
</P>
<P>
   In the other states:
</P>
<P>
   --Alabama Circuit Judge Roy Moore, who fought the American Civil
Liberties Union in 1995 to post the Ten Commandments in his
courtroom, was leading in the race for the GOP nomination for chief
justice of the state Supreme Court. With 11 percent of precincts
reporting, Moore had 9,588 votes votes, or 67 percent, in a
four-way race.
</P>
<P>
   Moore bucked Republican leaders by running for the seat, which
is being vacated by a justice forced to retire because he is past
70.
</P>
<P>
   --In Montana, Democratic farmer Brian Schweitzer made the high
price of prescription medicine the theme of his Senate campaign,
taking buses of seniors to Canada to highlight the price
differences. He was expected to win the nomination and face
two-term GOP Sen. Conrad Burns in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Also in Montana, three Democrats and two Republicans sought
their party nominations to replace Republican Gov. Mark Racicot,
forced by term limits to retire.
</P>
<P>
   In a bitter primary fight in New Jersey, 10-term Rep. Marge
Roukema was trailing 62 percent to 38 percent to conservative state
Assemblyman Scott Garrett. The returns did not include any votes
from her home base of Bergen County.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett, who lost a close fight with Roukema two years ago, got
$100,000 worth of support in ads from a conservative group.
</P>
<P>
   And two former GOP congressmen fought for the nomination to
challenge first-term Democratic Rep. Rush Holt. Mike Pappas lost to
Holt two years ago in part because of a ditty he sang about
impeachment on the House floor (''Twinkle, Twinkle, Kenneth
Starr''). He vied with former Rep. Dick Zimmer, a lawyer who
teaches at Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere:
</P>
<P>
   -- In New Mexico, three Republicans sought the nomination to
challenge three-term Democratic Sen. Jeff Bingaman.
</P>
<P>
   -- In Iowa, two Republicans sought the nomination to challenge
two-term Democratic Rep. Leonard Boswell.
</P>
<P>
   -- In the race for South Dakota's lone House seat, three
Democrats sought the nomination to challenge two-term Republican
Rep. John Thune.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-06-00 2117 </TRAILER>
