<HEADLINE> Kennedy GOP Opponent Clears Hurdle  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- A Republican whose campaign against Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy has been plagued by trouble officially won a spot on the
November ballot Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary of state's office approved 10,139 nominating
signatures for Jack E. Robinson, slightly more than the 10,000 he
needed. Robinson, a black businessman who made a fortune in
telecommunications, is making his first run for office.
</P>
<P>
   Libertarian candidate Carla Howell said Tuesday night she would
review Robinson's signatures to make sure they are legitimate. A
spokesman for Kennedy, a Democrat who has held the seat since 1962,
said Kennedy has no plans to challenge Robinson's signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Both Howell and Kennedy have well over the 10,000 margin.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's campaign has been through controversy from the start.
The state's top Republicans withdrew their support after
embarrassing details of his past were revealed, including his
arrest on drunken driving charges -- he was eventually cleared -- and
the fact that an ex-girlfriend had taken out a restraining order
against him.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody had a lot of laughs at my expense the last 90 days
so now let's get over that and get onto the issues,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
