<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin music king Tito Puente is laid to rest  </HEADLINE>
AP Photos
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANUET, N.Y. (AP) - Mambo king Tito Puente, whose music crossed
cultural and generational boundaries, was laid to rest Tuesday
following a private funeral Mass at St. Anthony's Catholic Church
in Rockland County.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was the best,'' the Rev. Lewis Gigante, told Newsday.
Gigante recalled knowing Puente from several decades ago in East
Harlem and the Bronx. He said that an era had died with Puente.
''His music was the best bridge to bring people together. He was
the Bach and the Beethoven of Latin music.''
</P>
<P>
   Puente, 77, died last Wednesday at NYU Medical Center. He had
recently been treated for an irregular heartbeat, according to his
agent, Eddie Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday and Monday, thousands of fans and fellow musicians
lined up outside a Manhattan funeral chapel to bid a fond farewell
to their beloved El Rey. He was recalled as a man who was a source
of pride, especially to people of Puerto Rican descent.
</P>
<P>
   In expressing their love and admiration, mourners held Puerto
Rican flags, wore T-shirts emblazoned with his image and listened
to his music while trading memories of the flamboyant percussionist
and bandleader outside Riverside Chapel.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have lost a brother, and like the rest of the world, I am
deeply saddened,'' fellow timbale player Jimmy Sabater said Sunday.
''This is a great loss.... He was the king immortalized,'' said
George Padilla.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-06-00 2146 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000606.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bob Hope To Go Home by Thursday  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RANCHO MIRAGE, Calif. (AP) -- Bob Hope is likely to be out of the
hospital and headed home by Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The 97-year-old entertainer ''responded with a resounding,
'Yes!''' when asked if he would like to go home, Dr. Gary
Annunziata said Tuesday. He said Hope likely would be released
within 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Hope was taken to Eisenhower Regional Medical Center in critical
condition with gastrointestinal bleeding last Thursday. The
entertainer's doctor marveled at Hope's quick recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is more awake, alert and talkative than I've seen him in a
long time,'' Annunziata said Tuesday. Hope was up and out of bed,
visiting with his wife Dolores.
</P>
<P>
   When he returns to his mountainside estate, Hope will continue
with a program of physical therapy to improve his strength and
motor coordination, the doctor said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.bobhope.com
</P>
</TEXT>
