<DOCNO> APW20000606.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corzine Leads Florio in N.J.  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Former investment banker Jon Corzine held a
wide lead over former Gov. Jim Florio in New Jersey's Democratic
Senate primary Tuesday, after the political newcomer spent a
record-shattering $33 million on his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With 29 percent of precincts reporting, Corzine led with 84,698
votes, or 62 percent. Florio drew 51,886 votes, or 38 percent.
Corzine was outpolling Florio by more than 3-1 in the vote-rich
Newark area, but only a few votes had been counted in Florio's home
base of Camden.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine has never held elected office but quickly gained
endorsements from top state political leaders, including the man
both he and Florio hope to replace, retiring three-term Democratic
Sen. Frank Lautenberg. The race was the highlight of primary voting
in six states Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Florio, seeking a return to politics after voters dumped him in
1993 at the end of just one term because he raised taxes by $2.8
billion, accused Corzine of trying to buy the seat.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's primary spending -- which could work out to as much as
$100 per vote -- shattered the previous U.S. record for an entire
Senate race -- $30 million spent by Republican Michael Huffington in
his losing 1994 bid for office in California.
</P>
<P>
   The former Goldman Sachs chairman unleashed a
$2-million-per-week blitz of TV commercials and poured hundreds of
