of all the money he put into it.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got a new face,'' Reiff said. ''Let's give him a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Rain throughout the day threatened to keep turnout low.
</P>
<P>
   The attention paid to Corzine's spending and his campaign
platforms, such as federal funding of college for students with B
averages or better and investing Social Security funds in the stock
market, dwarfed interest in the GOP primary for Lautenberg's seat.
</P>
<P>
   After GOP Gov. Christie Whitman said she would not run, four
lesser-known candidates stepped in.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. William Gormley was leading with 43 percent of the
total in a four-way race with Rep. Bob Franks, Essex County
Executive Jim Treffinger and Ramapo College professor Murray
Sabrin. The GOP has not won a Senate seat in New Jersey since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday also marked the end of the presidential primary season,
with contests in five of the six states, though they held little
import since George W. Bush and Al Gore locked up their nominations
back in March. The sixth state, Iowa, held its caucuses in January.
</P>
<P>
   In the other states:
</P>
<P>
   --Alabama Circuit Judge Roy Moore, who fought the American Civil
Liberties Union in 1995 to post the Ten Commandments in his
courtroom, was leading in the race for the GOP nomination for chief
justice of the state Supreme Court. With 11 percent of precincts
reporting, Moore had 9,588 votes votes, or 67 percent, in a
four-way race.
</P>
<P>
   Moore bucked Republican leaders by running for the seat, which
is being vacated by a justice forced to retire because he is past
70.
</P>
<P>
   --In Montana, Democratic farmer Brian Schweitzer made the high
price of prescription medicine the theme of his Senate campaign,
taking buses of seniors to Canada to highlight the price
differences. He was expected to win the nomination and face
two-term GOP Sen. Conrad Burns in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Also in Montana, three Democrats and two Republicans sought
their party nominations to replace Republican Gov. Mark Racicot,
forced by term limits to retire.
</P>
<P>
   In a bitter primary fight in New Jersey, 10-term Rep. Marge
Roukema pulled even with conservative state Assemblyman Scott
Garrett, who lost a close fight with Roukema two years ago. Garett
got $100,000 worth of support in ads from a conservative group.
</P>
<P>
   And two former GOP congressmen fought for the nomination to
challenge first-term Democratic Rep. Rush Holt. Rep. Dick Zimmer, a
lawyer who teaches at Princeton, led with 62 percent of the vote in
early returns against Mike Pappas, who lost to Holt two years ago
in part because of a ditty he sang about impeachment on the House
floor (''Twinkle, Twinkle, Kenneth Starr'').
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere:
</P>
<P>
   -- In New Mexico, three Republicans sought the nomination to
challenge three-term Democratic Sen. Jeff Bingaman.
</P>
<P>
   -- In Iowa, two Republicans sought the nomination to challenge
two-term Democratic Rep. Leonard Boswell.
</P>
<P>
   -- In the race for South Dakota's lone House seat, three
Democrats sought the nomination to challenge two-term Republican
Rep. John Thune.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
