<DOCNO> APW20000606.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-majority leader loses staff, prime office  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - What is the cost of attempting to topple the
speaker of the New York state Assembly?
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the failed coup by the ex-No. 2 in the chamber,
Michael Bragman, about $1.2 million a year in terms of staffers,
offices expenses and other expenses related to the post.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman said he was told Tuesday by an emissary from Silver that
all but two or three of his one-time staff of about 36 people would
be transferred away starting Thursday and he would be moved to a
much smaller office in the state Legislative Office Building as of
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of resources is clearly designed by Silver to ''punish
me'' for the failed coup attempt by ''beating on people, staff
people,'' Bragman said. But Bragman, a Democrat whose district
office is in North Syracuse, argued that it is unfair to take
members of his staff who have ''vast expertise'' in transportation,
workers' compensation and other issues and move them into undefined
new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't tell them where they'll be working, I can't tell them
what they will be doing,'' Bragman said. ''This is not based on how
intelligent you are or how hard you want to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Bragman lost the majority leader's title, his $34,500-a-year
stipend, his state Capitol office and a dozen of the majority
leader's staffers when his coup attempt was unfolding. He said the
additional cuts will mean the reduction of his staff from two dozen
to two or three, depending on how he wishes to allocate his
remaining budget.
</P>
<P>
   In dollars, Bragman said he was told he would be given $125,000
a year to run his offices, or prorated for the rest of 2000,
$70,000.
</P>
<P>
   That is very different from the budget Bragman formerly enjoyed.
In the 1998-99 state fiscal year, Bragman spent $1.36 million on
his office, far more than the average of about $304,000 of all
Assembly Democrats for that year.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman's previous spending is somewhat misleading, however.
Unlike other legislative leaders, he did not split up his costs
between the operations of his office as an individual legislator
and as majority leader. Other leaders list the expenses of their
appointed offices - such as the Finance Committee in the Senate or
the Ways and Means Committee in the Assembly - separately, lowering
the cost of running their offices as individual legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman said his district office gets about 300 calls a week
from constituents.
</P>
<P>
   ''We help,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Silver spokeswoman Patricia Lynch confirmed Bragman's loss of
about $1.2 million worth of staff and perks.
</P>
<P>
   ''These were perks what were attached to the majority leader's
position and since he is no longer majority leader, those
additional resources need to be held for the new and the next
majority leader,'' she said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It will be up to Bragman to choose which employees he wants to
retain on his staff, according to Lynch. The others will start to
work for the Assembly's ''central staff'' doing projects for the
Democratic majority, she said.
</P>
<P>
   No one will be fired, Lynch said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The speaker has guaranteed that the staff people will not lose
their jobs because of the attempted power play of their boss,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The office Bragman is being forced out of is on the prestigious
ninth floor of the Legislative Office Building where long-tenured,
powerful lawmakers have offices. His new office will be a
far-smaller space on the third floor of the same building where
low-tenured and minority party legislators have mostly been
assigned space.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman said the loss of resources shows the absolute power
Silver has and the need for the reforms in the Assembly which he
and other dissident Democrats are advocating for.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman suggested that legal action is one of the options he is
''reviewing,'' though courts in New York have been highly reluctant
to inject themselves into the activities of a coequal branch of
government, the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Silver said it is unlikely a new majority leader
will be selected until after the November elections for all seats
in the state Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd like to sit down and see the results of the election and
go with a majority leader at that point,'' the speaker told WROW-AM
radio in Albany. ''There are several deputies and assistants who
have been doing a very good job on the floor. At this point I think
we will wait for the start of the new legislative session.''
</P>
<P>
   Assuming his district returns him to Albany, Silver will also
face an election among Democrats if he is to retain the speakership
for the 2001-02 legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   The majority leader acts as a traffic cop in the Assembly,
bringing bills to the floor the ruling Democrats favor and calling
committee meetings. Assemblyman Clarence Norman of Brooklyn has
been filling in most of the time since Silver stripped Bragman of
his majority leader's title on May 17.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-06-00 2156 </TRAILER>
