<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, June 6, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
DOJ Official Criticizes Microsoft Response
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- A Justice Department spokeswoman today criticized Microsoft's
response to the DOJ's breakup plan in the anti-trust case. Gina Talamona says
the response, which came a day early than expected today, ''rehashes Microsoft's
old arguments, ignores the extensive violations found by the court, denies the
need for serious relief and grossly distorts our proposed remedy.'' In the
filing, Microsoft asked U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson to include
previously suggested language that would give a broken-up Microsoft more freedom
to enter into agreements with software developers and computer makers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Corzine Wins N.J. Senate Nomination
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Propelled from obscurity by his record-shattering $33
million campaign, retired investment banker Jon Corzine captured New Jersey's
Democratic Senate nomination today and ruined the comeback hopes of former Gov.
Jim Florio. With 38 percent of precincts reporting, Corzine led with 103,175
votes, or 60 percent. Florio drew 67,763 votes, or 40 percent. Corzine has never
held elected office but quickly gained endorsements from top state political
leaders, including the man both he and Florio hope to replace, retiring
three-term Democratic Sen. Frank Lautenberg. The race was the highlight of
primary voting in six states today.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Serb Aide Says CIA Behind Slaying
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A top aide to Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic on Tuesday claimed that the CIA was behind the slaying of an adviser
to Montenegro's pro-Western president. U.S. officials called the charge absurd.
Montenegrin President Milo Djukanovic is at odds with Milosevic's government
over economic and political issues. Montenegro and Serbia make up Yugoslavia.
Some officials in Montenegro have accused Yugoslav authorities of complicity in
the killing of National Security Adviser Goran Zugic a week ago. Zugic was one
of Djukanovic closest associates.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Violence Intensifies in Solomons
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) -- Fighting between rival rebel factions on the
Solomon Islands intensified Wednesday, with one group using a stolen gunboat to
fire cannon rounds at coastal villages and hitting a school, New Zealand
officials said. There were no reports of casualties from the shelling, which
marked a major escalation of the weaponry being used in the dispute between
rival islanders. The 1{-year-old confrontation on the Pacific island nation
exploded into a governmental crisis on Monday, with one rebel group seizing the
prime minister.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cos. Propose Web Transactions Guide
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Seven leading Internet and electronic commerce companies
proposed guidelines today to protect consumers who make purchases online and
help them resolve disputes with merchants. The Electronic Commerce and Consumer
Protection Group, which includes America Online, AT&AMP;T, Dell, IBM, Microsoft,
Network Solutions and Time Warner, proposed the new guidelines at the start of a
two-day Federal Trade Commission workshop on online business. ''Consumers should
be empowered to deal only with reputable merchants, under terms that make them
comfortable,'' said Roger Cochetti, a spokesman for the group.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mideast Peace Talks To Resume
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel and the Palestinians agreed Tuesday to resume
negotiations in the Washington area early next week after a two-week lapse, but
despite prodding by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright they remained far
apart on terms of a settlement. The future of Jerusalem, one of the main issues,
has not been formally discussed, a senior U.S. official said. On the Palestinian
side, Yasser Arafat demanded Israel make good on a promised third pullback on
the West Bank and said Israel should quit the West Bank under 1967 and 1973 U.N.
Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell slightly in early trading. The Nikkei Stock
Average shed 42.75 points to 17,127.33. In New York on Tuesday, the Dow Jones
industrial average fell 79.73 to close at 10,735.57. On the NYSE, advancing
issues outnumbered decliners 1,524-1,396. The Nasdaq composite index fell 65.39
to 3,756.37.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lewis Testifies in Murder Trial
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Ray Lewis placed a laser pointer in his fist and showed
jurors Tuesday how his friend held a knife and described striking a man
repeatedly during street brawl that left two men dead after the Super Bowl. The
NFL star, testifying one day after murder charges against him were dropped, said
he asked Joseph Sweeting what happened in the hours after the Jan. 31 fight.
Lewis said the fight, which happened outside an Atlanta club after a Super Bowl
party, was over so quickly he couldn't tell if Sweeting or defendant Reginald
Oakley -- who still face murder charges -- had stabbed the two men.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY
</SUBHEAD>
