<DOCNO> APW20000606.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Power Outage Stalls U.S. Cup Game  </HEADLINE>
By JIMMY GOLEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass. (AP) -- A power outage during a heavy rainstorm
delayed a U.S. Cup game between the United States and Ireland for
22 minutes before play resumed on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The score was 1-1 when the stadium lights went out at Foxboro
Stadium, sending the field into darkness. The game clock continued
to run, and some billboards remained illuminated with auxiliary
power.
</P>
<P>
   Power was restored about 10 minutes later, but the lights needed
time to warm up and the game resumed at 9:53 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   Wind whipped at up to 35 mph and driving rainstorm drenched the
crowd, but the field remained clean and the footing appeared sure
before the outage, which organizers could not immediately explain.
</P>
<P>
   A blown transformer near the stadium delayed the NFL's 1997 AFC
Championship game between the New England Patriots and Jacksonville
Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   Although the game was only an exhibition, U.S. coach Bruce Arena
is using the U.S. Cup to pick the squad that will compete in World
Cup qualifying starting next month.
</P>
<P>
   Ireland took a 1-0 lead when Domonic Foley converted a bicycle
kick pass from Stephen McPhail in the 31st minute. Foley also
scored in Ireland's first game, a 2-2 tie with Mexico on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans tied it in the 68th minute when Ante Razov got
past the defense -- perhaps so far that he should have been called
offsides -- and bounced a pass from Earnie Stewart into the net.
</P>
<P>
   Cobi Jones entered the game as a substitute in the 65th minute,
tying him with Marcelo Balboa for the U.S. record of 128
international appearances.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team, which beat South Africa 4-0 on Saturday, will
play Mexico at Giants Stadium in East Rutherford, N.J., on Sunday.
Ireland tied Mexico 2-2 on Sunday and plays South Africa at Giants
Stadium on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite heading into the wind, Ireland was able to capitalize in
the first half. McPhail got the ball in a crowd about 30 yards out
and wheeled it to Foley, who snuck behind U.S. defender C.J. Brown
10 yards from the goal and booted it past goalkeeper Brad Friedel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
