<DOCNO> APW20000606.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study finds 20-somethings want fun, sex -- not marriage  </HEADLINE>
By LINDA A. JOHNSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Are romance and marriage dead? Not exactly,
but they're clearly out of favor among ''20-somethings,'' according
to a study that found young adults are focusing on fun, casual sex
and low-commitment relationships, rather than courtship and
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   The National Marriage Project at Rutgers University in New
Brunswick surveyed never-married men and women age 21 through 29 in
Atlanta, Chicago, Dallas, Los Angeles and northern New Jersey for
its new study, dubbed ''Sex Without Strings, Relationships Without
Rings.''
</P>
<P>
   The study, released Tuesday, was based on results of separate
''focus group'' interviews of men and women, about 10 to 12 of each
sex in the five areas, along with lengthy questionnaires filled out
by the participants. The small number of people studied aren't
statistically representative of that population, but this pilot
study will be followed with a large national one next year,
according to David Popenoe, co-director of the three-year-old
project.
</P>
<P>
   ''We put this out as a special report because the material
seemed so compelling,'' said Popenoe, a sociology professor at
Rutgers.
</P>
<P>
   None of the interview subjects were college graduates or
currently in a four-year degree program, because most other studies
on such issues have surveyed college seniors or graduates, he said.
Rutgers focused on the non-college crowd because, Popenoe said,
it's roughly 75 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you want to look at what's happening in the country, this
is the group you want to look at,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The study revealed nearly identical goals among 20-something men
and women: achieving financial independence and buying a home
before marriage - and delaying marriage indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ''They tend to look at marriage not as a wealth-building thing,
but as an economic risk,'' because of the high costs associated
with divorce, Popenoe said.
</P>
<P>
   Among those in their late 20s, though, there was a difference.
The men still wanted the single life; the women were getting more
serious about finding a husband, but more disenchanted about their
chances of landing a good one.
</P>
<P>
   ''The women were very pessimistic and they had grown very
distrustful of men,'' Popenoe said.
</P>
<P>
   One reason he suggested was that the female participants ''were
quite presentable,'' but the men surveyed were ''considerably more
immature and lacking in goal orientation.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the participants were more likely to see the purpose
of marriage as personal satisfaction, not raising children
together. Many of the men did not want any children, and both sexes
saw it as OK to have a child outside of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many of the women were seriously thinking about single
motherhood as an option, although not an ideal one.
</P>
<P>
   ''In some cases, they're picking men out as sperm donors,''
Popenoe said.
</P>
<P>
   The study found several other significant shifts from past
attitudes, based on trends found in national social surveys, with
the participants likely to:
</P>
<P>
   -favor living together before or instead of marriage;
</P>
<P>
   -identify fear of divorce as the key reason to postpone or avoid
marriage;
</P>
<P>
   -idealize marriage, saying they wanted a ''soul mate,'' despite
saying they see marriage as difficult work;
</P>
<P>
   -support marriage preparation and relationship education as a
good way to prevent unhappy marriages and divorce.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although the study participants expect their future marriages
to last a lifetime and to fulfill their deepest emotional and
spiritual needs, they are involved in a mating culture that may
make it more difficult to achieve this lofty goal,'' said Barbara
Dafoe Whitehead, the project's other co-director.
</P>
<P>
   The ''Sex Without Strings'' report is part of a larger study,
the project's second annual report on the health of marriage in
America, called ''The State of Our Unions: 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Http://marriage.rutgers.edu/2000.htm	   
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
