<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Republican Senate to take up hate crime bill  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The New York state Senate appears ready to
abandon its long-held opposition to a law to stiffen penalties
committed on the basis of a victim's race, gender, age, religion
and sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-led Senate planned to vote on a measure Wednesday
proposed by Gov. George Pataki to push the penalties for so-called
hate crimes up one notch in severity.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a person facing a Class A misdemeanor charge, which
carries up to one year in jail, would be sentenced as if the crime
was a Class E felony if a defendant's intent to commit a hate crime
is proven. That person would face up to four years in prison under
the heightened penalties provision.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of a law say New York and South Carolina are
currently the only states on the East Coast without a bias crime
law.
</P>
<P>
   Majority Leader Joseph Bruno said Tuesday that ''times have
changed and the message probably ought to be out there'' that bias
crimes will not be tolerated in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly passed a somewhat more expansive bill this year in
which proof of the intent of a defendant to commit a hate crime
does not have to be present.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said he was happy Senate Republicans had relented and
decided to consider bias crime legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that is a major step forward,'' Pataki said Tuesday.
''It is something I have been working on and striving for since the
first day I got elected governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, gay groups hailed the Senate's apparent willingness to
pass the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a historic victory over hate and anti-gay prejudice,''
said Matt Foreman, executive director of the Empire State Pride
Agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrat-dominated state Assembly has approved hate crimes
bills for 11 straight years and is prepared to reconcile its latest
bill with the one the Senate will adopt, said Patricia Lynch, a
spokeswoman for Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblywoman Deborah Glick, a Manhattan Democrat and the
Assembly's only openly gay member, said she was ''absolutely
certain'' one bill acceptable to the Assembly, Senate and governor
can be worked out by the end of the legislative session later this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Foreman credited impassioned speeches by Sen. Thomas Duane about
bias-related assaults Duane has suffered for shifting ''the terms
of the debate from the abstract to the personal.'' Duane is the
only openly gay member of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Though he will allow the Senate to vote on a bias crime bill,
Bruno hardly sounded enthusiastic about the measure Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has been ''totally distorted'' for political purposes,
he grumbled, and become an issue of ''symbolism'' that is detached
from reality. Crime has been going down in New York and penalties
going up for the victims of all crime, regardless of the criminals'
motivation, Bruno said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't believe that a bias or hate bill by itself is going to
do anything to reduce crime,'' he said. ''But I believe that the
message that we're focusing on people who have malice in their
hearts or hate or a bias towards an individual or group ... maybe
the time has come for us to send out there.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. David Paterson, a Manhattan Democrat who first
introduced a hate crimes bill in 1987, said ambivalence is the
wrong signal for Bruno to send about the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ''If public servants aren't going to stand behind this they are
sending a subliminal message to prosecutors that they don't have to
pay attention to it,'' Paterson said. ''To me, it is a lot better
if they would embrace the legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruno's doubts about the bill show ''what a long way we have to
go'' in convincing New Yorkers about the wisdom of anti-bias crime
legislation, Paterson.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear how many of the 36 Republicans in the Senate
would vote for the measure. Thirty-one votes are needed for
passage, and most, if not all, of the 25 Democrats in the chamber
are expected to vote for the hate crimes bill.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno himself said he wasn't sure he would vote for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Post first reported Tuesday that Senate Republicans
would allow a vote on the bias crime bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-06-00 2217 </TRAILER>
