<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Rebels Closer to Release  </HEADLINE>
By CLARENCE ROY-MACAULAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Sierra Leone's feared rebels have
moved 21 U.N. peacekeepers closer to the Liberian border,
apparently in preparation to release them, a U.N. spokesman said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian peacekeepers had been surrounded by rebels for about
three weeks in the town of Quiva, about 170 miles east of the
capital, Freetown. They were moved Monday in two vehicles to
Pendembu, about 10 miles to the northeast.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials believed the move was the ''last phase'' before
the peacekeepers would be transferred to the Liberian capital,
Monrovia, and then returned to the United Nations in Freetown, U.N.
spokesman David Wimhurst said.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels appeared to be acting on the instructions of Liberian
President Charles Taylor, who helped negotiate the release of 500
U.N. hostages via the same route, Wimhurst said.
</P>
<P>
   Two other peacekeepers who were previously thought to be in
Quiva had turned up among 234 U.N. soldiers and 10 unarmed
observers surrounded in the rebel stronghold of Kailahun, about 200
miles east of Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a Zambian peacekeeper who had been missing and
presumed dead made contact with pro-government forces in the north
on Monday and was now recovering at a Freetown hospital, Wimhurst
said. He had no further details.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolutionary United Front rebels killed tens of thousands
of civilians during the West African country's eight-year civil war
and maimed many more.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels signed a July peace accord with the government, but
reignited the conflict in early May, seizing the 500 U.N. hostages
and advancing toward the capital.
</P>
<P>
   About 320 peacekeepers were expected to arrive Tuesday from
Bangladesh, bringing the U.N. force in Sierra Leone to 11,850.
</P>
<P>
   The peacekeeping mission is expected to be boosted to 13,000
troops by the end of June, and U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
has called for an additional 3,500 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   As British soldiers prepare to pull out of Sierra Leone in
mid-June, the United Nations has promised a more robust response
from its peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are going to take very firm action to defend themselves
if hostile intent is show toward them, and to defend unarmed
civilians whenever their lives are endangered,'' U.N. military
spokesman Lt. Cmdr. Patrick Coker said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Sen. Judd Gregg agreed Tuesday to release
$50 million in U.S. funds for the peacekeeping operation after
receiving assurances from the administration that it no longer
envisions a role for rebel leader Foday Sankoh in efforts to reach
a new peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg, who is chairman of the Senate subcommittee overseeing
State Department expenditures, had been single-handedly holding up
the money. Sankoh was captured by pro-government forces last month
and is being held at an undisclosed location.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-06-00 2220 </TRAILER>
