<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. 1, Ireland 1  </HEADLINE>
By JIMMY GOLEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass. (AP) -- Ante Razov scored in the 68th minute as
the United States survived a nor'easter, a 22-minute power outage
and a deficit to tie Ireland 1-1 Tuesday night in the U.S. Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Wind whipped at up to 35 mph and a driving rainstorm drenched
the crowd, but the field remained clean and the footing appeared
sure before the outage in the 71st minute.
</P>
<P>
   The Foxboro Stadium lights went out, sending the field into
darkness. The game clock continued to run, and some billboards
remained illuminated with auxiliary power.
</P>
<P>
   Power was restored about 10 minutes later, but the lights needed
time to warm up and the game resumed at 9:53 p.m. EDT. Organizers
blamed the interruption on a brownout affecting Massachusetts
Electric customers in the area.
</P>
<P>
   A blown transformer near the stadium delayed the NFL's 1997 AFC
Championship game between the New England Patriots and Jacksonville
Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. coach Bruce Arena is using the U.S. Cup to pick the squad
that will compete in World Cup qualifying starting next month.
</P>
<P>
   Ireland (0-0-2 in the tournament) took a 1-0 lead when Domonic
Foley converted a bicycle-kick pass from Stephen McPhail in the
31st minute. Foley also scored in Ireland's first game, a 2-2 tie
with Mexico on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Razov then got behind the defense -- perhaps so far that he
should have been called offsides -- and bounced a pass from Earnie
Stewart into the net to tie it for the United States (1-0-1 in the
cup, 4-2-3 this year).
</P>
<P>
   The home team has never lost in seven games between Ireland and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Cobi Jones entered the game as a substitute in the 65th minute,
tying him with Marcelo Balboa for the U.S. record of 128
international appearances.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team, which beat South Africa 4-0 on Saturday, will
play Mexico at Giants Stadium in East Rutherford, N.J., on Sunday.
Ireland plays South Africa at Giants Stadium on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite heading into the wind, Ireland was able to capitalize in
the first half. McPhail got the ball in a crowd about 30 yards out
and wheeled it to Foley, who snuck behind U.S. defender C.J. Brown
10 yards from the goal and booted it past goalkeeper Brad Friedel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
