<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAS Needs Money to Avoid Crisis  </HEADLINE>
By TOM COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDSOR, Ontario (AP) -- A day after approving a new mission to
enhance democracy in Peru, the Organization of American States
heard Tuesday it was running out of money and members must pay what
they owe to keep it going.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign ministers attending the 30th general assembly of the
34-nation group echoed a call by Secretary General Cesar Gaviria of
Colombia for the OAS to reassess priorities and unlock spending
that has remained at $75 million a year under a 1995 mandate.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you don't review your 1995 decision, the OAS is going to be
extinguished very soon,'' Gaviria said. ''It's as simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   The OAS budget comes from annual assessments, known as quotas,
collected from each member. Six countries -- the United States,
Canada, Brazil, Mexico, Argentina and Venezuela -- together are
assessed more than 90 percent of the total, with the United States
asked to pay almost five times as much as anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   For this year, the U.S. quota was $44 million, while Canada had
the second largest quota at $9 million. Of the so-called big six,
Canada, Mexico, Argentina and Venezuela have paid their full quotas
for this year, while the United States owes $36 million and Brazil
its entire quota of $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials authorized to comment on the issue were attending
meetings Tuesday and not immediately available, according to the
office of the U.S. delegation.
</P>
<P>
   The OAS has received $26.6 million of the $73.7 million in year
2000 quotas so far.
</P>
<P>
   Gaviria said the OAS was struggling to maintain its programs and
activities, noting that nine of its offices in the hemisphere had
been closed in the past five years. He and others said the OAS was
under pressure to take a stronger role in hemispheric issues, such
as election observer missions and the special mission being sent to
Peru.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mandates cannot continue being given to the OAS without at the
same time increasing in real terms the resources we have at our
disposal,'' said Javier Murillo, the Bolivian foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
   A resolution passed Monday night created a new mandate -- sending
Gaviria and Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy to
Peru to assess ways to rebuild democracy following irregularities
in the recent election of President Alberto Fujimori to a third
straight term.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Organization of American States: http://www.oas.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
