<HEADLINE> Cubs 4, Diamondbacks 1  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Kevin Tapani took a shutout into the ninth inning
to lead the Chicago Cubs to a 4-1 victory over the Arizona
Diamondbacks, who lost their fourth straight game.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Augie Ojeda hit an RBI triple to spark a three-run fifth
off Armando Reynoso (4-5). The Diamondbacks have lost four straight
for the first time since June 20-23, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Tapani (4-6) pitched a five-hitter, allowing a solo homer to
Craig Counsell with one out in the ninth inning. It was Tapani's
second complete game this season. He also went the distance April
18 in a 4-3 loss to Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Tapani retired the first nine batters he faced before Tony
Womack singled to lead off the fourth. Damian Miller reached on an
infield single in the sixth and as did Craig Counsell leading off
the seventh. Turner Ward also doubled with one out in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Tapani struck out seven -- including Luis Gonzalez three times --
and did not walk a batter. He now has worked at least seven innings
in each of his last eight starts and 10 of his last 11 outings.
</P>
<P>
   Reynoso lost for the second time in his last seven starts,
giving up three runs and six hits over 4 2-3 innings. He struck out
a season-high seven.
</P>
<P>
   Damon Buford walked to lead off the Cubs fifth and Ojeda tripled
into the right-field corner to make it 1-0. One out later, Eric
Young was hit in the left shoulder by a pitch and Joe Girardi
singled to score Ojeda and make it 2-0. Mark Grace then singled to
drive in Young.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the Cubs' seventh, Young walked, stole second,
advanced on a wild pitch by Russ Springer and scored on Girardi's
double to make it 4-0.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Tapani's career low-hit complete game was a one-hitter
Sept. 16, 1997, against Cincinnati. ... Ojeda, called up May 31
from Triple-A Iowa, started his third straight game at short. The
Cubs' other shortstops, Ricky Gutierrez (separated shoulder) and
Jose Nieves (strained hamstring), are on the disabled list. ...
Arizona broadcaster Rod Allen's son Rod Allen Jr. was drafted by
Cincinnati in the 34th round of the amateur draft.
</P>
