<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, June 6, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Microsoft Files Breakup Response
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. filed a fresh response to the Justice
Department's breakup plan a day earlier than expected, clearing the way for a
federal judge to make a final ruling in the protracted antitrust case. In the
filing, Microsoft asked U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson to include
previously suggested language that would give a broken-up Microsoft more freedom
to enter into agreements with software developers and computer makers. The DOJ
and 17 states have pushed to have Microsoft broken up into two separate
companies -- one to market and produce Windows, and the other to handle
Microsoft Office and other applications software, along with the Internet
Explorer Web browser.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Corzine Wins N.J. Senate Nomination
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Retired investment banker Jon Corzine captured New
Jersey's Democratic Senate nomination today and ruined the comeback hopes of
former Gov. Jim Florio. With 46 percent of precincts reporting, Corzine led with
124,405 votes, or 60 percent. Florio drew 83,095 votes, or 40 percent. Corzine
has never held elected office but quickly gained endorsements from top state
political leaders, including the man both he and Florio hope to replace,
retiring three-term Democratic Sen. Frank Lautenberg.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Serbs, NATO Clash After Grenades
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GRACANICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Serbs angry over a grenade attack swarmed
around a British general Tuesday, prompting his bodyguards open fire to scare
the crowd. The clash left one person wounded and increased tensions in the
already restive Serb community. The shooting came during a melee that was
touched off by the grenade explosion as furious Serbs attacked passing ethnic
Albanians and peacekeepers, leaving at least 11 more people injured. The outrage
in this Serb enclave comes after a surge of attacks Kosovo's Serb community
claims are intended to drive them and other minorities from the province.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
National D-Day Museum Opens in La.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- World War II veterans looked back to 56 years ago and
others paused to honor them today at the opening of the National D-Day Museum.
Crowds came to the Superdome to watch veterans parade past with a flyover by 54
military planes as the museum officially opened on the 56th anniversary of the
invasion to liberate Europe from Nazi terror. In the front row at the opening
were eight Medal of Honor winners, backed by hundreds of dignitaries, elected
officials and veterans who paid homage to those who fell.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cos. Propose Web Transactions Guide
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Seven leading Internet and electronic commerce companies
proposed guidelines today to protect consumers who make purchases online and
help them resolve disputes with merchants. The Electronic Commerce and Consumer
Protection Group, which includes America Online, AT&AMP;T, Dell, IBM, Microsoft,
Network Solutions and Time Warner, proposed the new guidelines at the start of a
two-day Federal Trade Commission workshop on online business. ''Consumers should
be empowered to deal only with reputable merchants, under terms that make them
comfortable,'' said Roger Cochetti, a spokesman for the group.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mideast Peace Talks To Resume
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel and the Palestinians agreed Tuesday to resume
negotiations in the Washington area early next week after a two-week lapse, but
despite prodding by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright they remained far
apart on terms of a settlement. The future of Jerusalem, one of the main issues,
has not been formally discussed, a senior U.S. official said. On the Palestinian
side, Yasser Arafat demanded Israel make good on a promised third pullback on
the West Bank and said Israel should quit the West Bank under 1967 and 1973 U.N.
Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Activists Demand Sex Equality
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Women's rights activists demanded today that countries
which have promised to promote equality between the sexes repeal laws that
discriminate against women, including those that allow rapists to escape
punishment by marrying their victims. Equality Now, a nonprofit organization,
has launched a campaign to abolish the dozens of laws in penal codes and
constitutions ''which are fundamentally inconsistent with the basic human right
to equality,'' said Monique Widyono, the New York-based organization's
co-director.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell slightly in early trading. The Nikkei Stock
Average shed 42.75 points to 17,127.33. In New York, the Dow Jones industrial
average fell 79.73 to close at 10,735.57. The Nasdaq composite index fell 65.39
to 3,756.37.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Indians Defeat Brewers 4-2
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- David Justice hit his 250th home run and Chuck Finley
pitched a seven-hitter as the Cleveland Indians beat the Milwaukee Brewers 4-2
tonight for their fourth straight win. Justice, who homered twice Monday, hit a
420-foot drive off John Snyder (0-2).
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY
</SUBHEAD>
