<HEADLINE> Donor's Ex-Aide Pleads Guilty  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- A former aide to a Democratic donor pleaded
guilty Tuesday to obstructing a Justice Department investigation
into campaign contributions made by her boss, David Chang.
</P>
<P>
   The plea by Audrey Yu came on the day she and Chang were to
stand trial. Chang pleaded guilty Friday to illegally donating
$53,700 to the successful 1996 Senate campaign of then-Rep. Robert
Torricelli.
</P>
<P>
   Like Chang, Yu has agreed to cooperate with the Campaign
Financing Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   Yu, 32, faces six to 12 months in prison but could get probation
for pleading guilty to a single charge of conspiring with Chang to
obstruct justice.
</P>
<P>
   As part of her plea, Yu admitted that she lied to a federal
grand jury last year when she said she did not see shredded
documents at the offices of one of Chang's companies.
</P>
<P>
   Chang operates several trading companies in Torricelli's former
congressional district.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli spokesman Richard McGrath said he had no comment on
Yu because her activities did not involve the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Yu is among 25 people charged by the task force. Six, not
including Yu, have admitted wrongdoing regarding Torricelli
fund-raising efforts. None of the six has implicated the New Jersey
Democrat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
