<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hicks Named Loyola, Md. Hoops Coach  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- Scott Hicks, the men's basketball coach of the
State University of New York at Albany, was introduced Tuesday as
the head coach at Loyola College.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel strongly that we can achieve a very high level in the
years to come on the basketball court,'' Hicks said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, 34, has compiled a 131-95 record in eight seasons as a
collegiate head coach.
</P>
<P>
   He spent the past three seasons as Albany's head coach, leading
the Great Danes to an 11-17 record last season, Albany's first as a
Division I independent.
</P>
<P>
   ''Scott is a great young basketball mind, and he has been
successful at every juncture of his career,'' Loyola athletic
director Joe Boylan said.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks was a graduate assistant coach at Syracuse before he
became the head coach at LeMoyne College, which he led to the New
England Collegiate Conference championship in 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, a native of Oneida, N.Y., is a 1988 graduate of LeMoyne,
where he was captain of the 1988 team, which went 24-6.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Loyola announced that Dino Gaudio resigned after three
years as head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Gaudio won a Metro Atlantic Athletic Conference tournament game
in each of his first two seasons at Loyola. He left after a 7-21
record last season to become an assistant at Xavier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
