<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda, Uganda Agree to Cease-Fire  </HEADLINE>
By HRVOJE HRANJSKI
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISANGANI, Congo (AP) -- After two days of fierce fighting,
Rwandan and Ugandan troops on Tuesday agreed to a U.N.-brokered
cease-fire in a northern Congolese city that both sides consider
strategic.
</P>
<P>
   Only sporadic gunfire could be heard in the Congo River port of
Kisangani after the cease-fire took effect, the third such attempt
by a U.N. mission here to stop the fighting between the two
erstwhile allies in a 22-month war against Congolese President
Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni said Uganda would not complete
a planned withdrawal from the town without a U.N.-supervised
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   Rwandan and Ugandan armies have clashed repeatedly in Kisangani,
a city both view as strategic for resupplying their troops
elsewhere in Congo. Both armies were in the process of withdrawing
on Monday when Ugandan artillery pounded Rwandan positions in the
city. Ugandan officials suspected the Rwandan Patriotic Army of
firing a rocket at one of their vehicles and provoking the
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The Rwandan army denied the charge, and said the incident was
staged as an excuse to bring Ugandan troops back into the city and
regain positions lost in fighting in August and last month.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, preliminary talks began Tuesday in the nearby west
African nation of Benin, but without the participation of the
Congolese government.
</P>
<P>
   Delegations from the two major rebel factions, the Ugandan
foreign minister and some civil society representatives attended
the opening session of the meeting convened by international
mediator Ketumile Masire, the former president of Botswana. The
talks are aimed at deciding a venue, planning an agenda and working
out logistical problems for a national dialogue on Congo's
political future envisaged in last year's cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila, however, was not represented. The Congolese government
would not ''sit down at the same table as the instigators of
massacres,'' Foreign Minister Abdoulaye Yerodia said Monday in
Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
   After ferocious artillery bombardment that left at least four
civilians dead, Rwandan troops controlled most of downtown
Kisangani and halted the Ugandan advance across the Tshopo River
bridge.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. military observers said the Ugandan troops had crossed the
bridge on Monday in an attempt to move toward Kisangani, but had
faced Rwandan units that put up a fight.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials evacuated their headquarters to a Roman Catholic
church compound after two mortar rounds landed near their house on
Monday, they said. Kisangani, Congo's third largest city in the
middle of a thick tropical forest, was plunged into darkness after
one of the shells reportedly damaged the only power station.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're hoping they will respect this cease-fire. It's a third
cease-fire since yesterday,'' said Maj. Sissoko Ramadan, one of the
U.N. military observers stationed here as part of a peace plan
signed in August between Kabila and the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, which was also signed by Rwanda and Uganda
as well as Kabila's allies from Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia, the
foreign troops are to withdraw from Congo under the supervision of
5,537-strong U.N. force. So far, more than 100 unarmed U.N.
military observers have deployed in Congo and the remainder are
expected in July.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated gunshots pierced the otherwise quiet night in
Kisangani, where most residents took cover in their homes. Ramadan
said it might take a while before the cease-fire order reached all
units.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the two East African neighbors have
deteriorated since they went into Congo to back up a rebellion
against Kabila in August 1998. They have differed over the conduct
of war and which of the three rebel groups to support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-06-00 2316 </TRAILER>
