<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujimori to OAS: Don't Question Win  </HEADLINE>
By MONTE HAYES
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- President Alberto Fujimori said Tuesday that
the decision of the Organization of American States not to impose
sanctions against his government after his controversial
re-election was ''a triumph for Peru.''
</P>
<P>
   Defending his government in his first interview since the OAS
announced its decision, Fujimori told The Associated Press that it
was an ''imperfect democracy'' that he was working to improve.
</P>
<P>
   Looking like a man confident that events were going his way,
Fujimori said he did not foresee serious problems with the United
States, which has sharply criticized the fairness of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''I expect our relationship with the United States to continue
without problems and even to be strengthened. We will do our
best,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The OAS on Monday agreed to work on strengthening democracy in
Peru but stopped short of questioning the country's tainted
presidential election or imposing sanctions. Instead it resolved to
send a high-level mission to Peru to work on strengthening
democratic institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, Fujimori said he would welcome the OAS mission
and would work with it but would not accept its questioning his
re-election victory.
</P>
<P>
   ''The objective of the OAS is to promote and consolidate
representative democracy, respecting the principle of
nonintervention,'' Fujimori told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The OAS general assembly voted Monday to send a mission composed
of its secretary general, Cesar Gaviria, and Canadian Foreign
Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign ministers debated what course of action to take
after a May 28 presidential runoff election that was boycotted by
Fujimori's opponent, who claimed it would be fraudulent
</P>
<P>
   In Buenos Aires, Argentine President Fernando de la Rua
expressed support for the OAS mission, but suggested any economic
sanctions on Peru would serve no useful purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Sanctions ''aren't going to hurt the electoral process, just the
people,'' he said. But de la Rua echoed many Latin American leaders
in expressing concern about the tainted re-election of Fujimori.
</P>
<P>
   ''What worries me most is what has gone on in this electoral
process,'' he said in the interview at the Government House in
Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori said the outcome of the OAS meeting was neither a
defeat nor a victory for his government.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the OAS election observer mission that left Peru
two days before the May 28 ballot concluded that the election
process was characterized by merely by ''irregularities, not
fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   Axworthy said Gaviria and he would go to Peru before Fujimori's
July 28 inauguration, when opposition groups plan to hold a giant
protest rally in Lima. Specific issues they will study include
reforming the electoral process and bolstering freedom of the
press.
</P>
<P>
   Debate before the OAS vote pitted Peru and some Latin American
allies that oppose foreign intervention in election issues against
the United States and others seeking a harsh response to
irregularities in the Peruvian voting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-06-00 2326 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
