<HEADLINE> Twins 3, Astros 1  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL A. LUTZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- Jose Lima took a two-hitter into the eighth
inning, then lost his eighth consecutive decision as the Minnesota
Twins rallied with a three-run eighth inning to beat the Houston
Astros 3-1 Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Lima (1-8), on the longest losing streak of his career, hasn't
won since beating Pittsburgh on April 5 in his first start of the
season. He didn't allow a home run for only the third time in 12
starts, but that wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   With Houston leading 1-0, Jacque Jones and Midre Cummings
singled leading off the eighth, Denny Hocking sacrificed and Yorkis
Perez relieved.
</P>
<P>
   Cristian Guzman's grounder scored Jones with the tying run, Matt
Lawton doubled for a 2-1 lead and David Ortiz followed with an RBI
single.
</P>
<P>
   Johan Santana (1-2) got his first major league win, allowing
three hits in five innings, including Ken Caminiti's RBI double in
the third.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Guardado, Minnesota's fourth pitcher, got three outs for
his third save in as many chances, completing a six-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   It was just the second time in 30 games at Enron Field that both
teams failed to hit any home runs. The other was an April 9 game
against Philadelphia. There have been 105 homers at Enron this
year, 13 short of last season's total in the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota starter Eric Milton was bruised on his left lower leg
when hit by Craig Biggio's liner leading off the first. Milton left
after the second inning and the Twins said he was day to day.
</P>
<P>
   Lima, 21-10 last season, retired his first 10 batters and didn't
allow a hit until Lawton's fourth-inning single. Ortiz singled
leading off the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Lima was charged with two runs and four hits in 7 1-3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Moises Alou returned to the Astros' lineup in left field after
missing eight games with a tight left quadriceps. He went 1-for-4
with a second-inning double.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Lawton leads the Twins with 21 multihit games. ... The four
runs matched the fewest at Enron (Colorado's 3-1 win on May 8). ...
Perez allowed both inherited runners to score after allowing one of
his first 11 this year. ... Lima had his longest outing of the
season and allowed his fewest hits.
</P>
</TEXT>
