<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Braves 7, Blue Jays 6  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL NEWBERRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Rafael Furcal drove in the winning run with a
one-out double in the ninth inning as the Atlanta Braves rallied
from a three-run deficit to beat the Toronto Blue Jays 7-6 Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The game dragged on for 3 hours, 44 minutes on an unseasonably
cool night. There were 18 walks -- 10 by the Blue Jays, including
two with the bases-loaded, and eight by the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan led off the ninth with a single off John Frascatore
(1-2) and moved to second on Javy Lopez's dribbler in front of the
plate. Bobby Bonilla was walked intentionally before Furcal lined a
drive to the gap in left-center.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Remlinger (2-1) picked up the win with a scoreless ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Woodward homered for the second night in a row, following
up a three-run homer Monday night that sent the Blue Jays on their
way to a 9-3 victory in the series opener.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays led 6-3 after Jose Cruz Jr.'s RBI single in the
sixth. But the Braves, who had lost three of their previous four,
battled back with runs in each of the next three innings. Walt
Weiss, who took Chipper Jones' spot in the batting order, tied it
up with a sacrifice fly in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   One day after sending closer John Rocker to the minors, the
Braves received a scare in the sixth inning when Jones, last year's
National League MVP, crumpled to the ground after stepping
awkwardly on second base.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who was trying to stop at the bag on a grounder up the
middle, remained on the ground for several minutes with an
anguished look on his face. He finally managed to limp off the
field with what appeared to be a sprained ankle. X-rays were
negative.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves went ahead in the first on Jones' 13th homer of the
season, a 428-foot drive into the right-field seats. Jones drove in
another run with a bases-loaded walk against Paul Quantrill in the
sixth before he was injured.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward hit a two-run homer in the third to give the Blue Jays
a 4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Andruw Jones had two RBIs for the Braves. Toronto's Shannon
Stewart went 3-for-5, including a run-scoring single in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Braves starter Tom Glavine had a miserable game, throwing 136
pitches in just six innings. He walked six in a game for the first
time since Aug. 4, 1996, at Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Jays starter Frank Castillo had a career-high seven walks,
including one to Andruw Jones with the bases loaded in the fourth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Greene made his first appearance as the Blue Jays catcher
this season after Albert Castillo was thrown out of the game in the
fifth for arguing a called third strike.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto's other catcher, Darrin Fletcher, was supposed to be
available only for pinch-hitting duty after straining his right
shoulder making a throw Sunday. But even he was needed before the
night was over, entering in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Toronto had won four straight over the Braves. ... Chipper
Jones' homer marked the first time in four games that Toronto
didn't open the scoring. ... Glavine had two sacrifice bunts,
giving him 130 for his career. He eclipsed the Atlanta Braves
record of 129 set by Phil Niekro. ... Jason Marquis, the
21-year-old pitcher who replaced Rocker on the Braves' roster, made
his first major league appearance and threw a scoreless inning. ...
Atlanta 2B Quilvio Veras left after the fifth inning with lower
back pain. X-rays were negative.
</P>
</TEXT>
