<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democrat Wins Mont. GOP Nomination  </HEADLINE>
By BOB ANEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELENA, Mont. (AP) -- Brian Schweitzer, a farmer and political
newcomer who made the high cost of prescription medicine the theme
of his campaign, easily won the Democratic nomination Tuesday to
challenge GOP Sen. Conrad Burns.
</P>
<P>
   Schweitzer held off John Driscoll, a well-known political figure
who challenged Democratic Sen. Max Baucus in 1990. Driscoll
conducted his low-key pitch mostly through his Web site, and did
little fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   With 12 percent of precincts reporting, Schweitzer had 13,069
votes, 67 percent, and Driscoll had 6,513 votes, 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Schweitzer, who promised to embarrass Congress into doing
something about the cost of medicine, orchestrated four bus trips
of senior citizens to Canada and Mexico to get their prescriptions
filled at up to half of what they would pay in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He also went on the attack against Burns, rapping his farm
policies and saying he cannot be trusted because he reneged on a
vow to spend only two terms in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Burns, who was unopposed Tuesday, withheld rebuttals and watched
donations flow in. At last count he had $3.5 million, almost five
times the $710,000 raised by Schweitzer.
</P>
<P>
   Montana voters also narrowed the field of candidates vying to
succeed Gov. Marc Racicot, a popular Republican who is barred from
seeking a third term.
</P>
<P>
   In the Democratic race, state Auditor Mark O'Keefe led two other
top state officials, Secretary of State Mike Cooney and Attorney
General Joe Mazurek.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, the choice was between Lt. Gov. Judy
Martz and Rob Natelson, a University of Montana law professor known
for conservative activism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-06-00 2344 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000606.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-06 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Marlins Bench Gonzalez  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Alex Gonzalez, hitting just .163 a year after
making the NL All-Star team, was benched by the Florida Marlins on
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been a struggle,'' Marlins manager John Boles said. ''It
just can't continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Boles inserted Dave Berg at shortstop for Tuesday's 4-3 loss to
the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who hit .277 with 14 home runs and 59 RBIs last year
as a rookie, was just 33-for-202 this year with one homer and 11
RBI. He struck out 38 times.
</P>
<P>
   His average and on-base percentage (.202) are the lowest in the
major leagues among regular starters.
</P>
<P>
   Boles has benched Gonzalez before for not hustling. Although
Gonzalez has been taking extra batting practice, the results
haven't improved.
</P>
<P>
   ''He works super hard,'' Boles said. ''It's past the point of
wishing and hoping he gets base hits here and there. We believe in
this guy, we believe in his future. We want him to build it back up
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, known for his stellar defense, has also made a
team-leading 12 errors in 54 games. Last year, he had 27 errors all
season
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll see what my hitting coach says and try it day by day,''
Gonzalez said of a new batting stance the coaching staff has him
working on.
</P>
<P>
   Berg, who is hitting .247, had an RBI double Tuesday, but
committed one error and misplayed another grounder that was ruled a
hit. Gonzalez got into the game as a pinch-runner in the ninth
inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
